# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: steam-powered-vessel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] An **aircraft carrier** is a warship designed to carry, launch, recover and support aircraft at sea, equipped with a full-length flight deck and hangar facilities that allow it to serve as a mobile, seagoing airbase.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Typically it is the capital ship of a fleet (known as a carrier battle group), as it allows a naval force to project seaborne air power far from national territory without depending on local airfields for the staging of aircraft operations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] While heavier fixed-wing aircraft such as airlifters, gunships and bombers have been launched from aircraft carriers, these aircraft do not often land on a carrier due to flight deck limitations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier, along with its onboard aircraft and defensive ancillary weapons, is the largest weapon system ever created.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] By their tactical prowess, mobility, autonomy and the variety of operational means, aircraft carriers are often the centerpiece of modern naval warfare, and have significant diplomatic influence in deterrence, command of the sea and air supremacy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the Second World War, the aircraft carrier has replaced the battleship in the role of flagship of a fleet, and largely transformed naval battles from gunfire to beyond-visual-range air strikes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies use several variants of the aircraft carrier, sometimes categorized as sub-types of aircraft carriers and sometimes as distinct types of aviation-capable ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft carriers may be classified according to the type of aircraft they carry and their operational assignments.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Navies have a variety of classification systems for their ships, and a definitive number of current aircraft carriers depends on the specific criteria.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] As of July 2026 there are 9 navies operating 24 active vessels designated by their respective navies as either an "Aircraft Carrier" or "Aircraft Cruiser".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] These range in tonnage from the United States' 100,000 tonne USS *Gerald R.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford* to Brazil's 21,000 tonne NAM *Atlantico*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of the types listed here are not strictly defined as aircraft carriers by some sources.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] A fleet carrier is intended to operate with the main fleet and usually provides an offensive capability.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] These are the largest carriers capable of fast speeds.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] By comparison, escort carriers were developed to provide defense for convoys of ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] They were smaller and slower with lower numbers of aircraft carried.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Most were built from mercantile hulls or, in the case of merchant aircraft carriers, were bulk cargo ships with a flight deck added on top.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Light aircraft carriers were fast enough to operate with the main fleet but of smaller size with reduced aircraft capacity.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Soviet aircraft carrier *Admiral Kusnetsov* was termed a "heavy aircraft-carrying cruiser".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was primarily a legal construct to avoid the limitations of the Montreux Convention preventing 'aircraft carriers' transiting the Turkish Straits between the Soviet Black Sea bases and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] These ships, while sized in the range of large fleet carriers, were designed to deploy alone or with escorts.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition to supporting fighter aircraft and helicopters, they provide both strong defensive weaponry and heavy offensive missiles equivalent to a guided-missile cruiser.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The appellation "supercarrier" is not an official designation with any national navy, but a term used predominantly by the media and typically when reporting on larger and more advanced carrier types.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] It is also used when comparing carriers of various sizes and capabilities, both current and past.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] It was first used by *The New York Times* in 1938, in an article about the Royal Navy's HMS *Ark Royal*, that had a length of 800 feet (244 m), a displacement of 22,000 tons and was designed to carry 72 aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since then, aircraft carriers have consistently grown in size, both in length and displacement, as well as improved capabilities; in defense, sensors, electronic warfare, propulsion, range, launch and recovery systems, number and types of aircraft carried and number of sorties flown per day.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first aircraft carrier over 80,000 tonnes full-load displacement was the USS Forrestal launched in 1954.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] In total, the US Navy has had 5 different classes of aircraft carrier of this size definition, the Forrestal class, Kitty Hawk class, the Enterprise class, the Nimitz class and Gerald R Ford Class, two of which were conventional steam-powered and three nuclear-powered.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] USS *Enterprise*, launched in 1960, was the first carrier over 90,000 tonnes full load displacement and *Nimitz*, launched in 1972, was the first over 100,000 tonnes displacement.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] A total of 22 supercarriers have been launched by the US Navy since 1954, with 11 currently in service.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Both China (Type 003) and the United Kingdom (Queen Elizabeth class) have carriers in service with displacements from 80,000 to 85,000 tonnes and lengths from 280 to 320 meters (920 to 1,050 ft) which are described as "supercarriers".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] France is also developing a new aircraft carrier (PANG) which is to have a full load displacement of 80,000 tonnes and will be considered a supercarrier.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The largest supercarrier in service as of 2024 is the US Navy's USS Gerald R.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Ford, with full load displacement of around 100,000 tons, length of 337 meters (1,106 ft) and capabilities that exceed those of any other class.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] A US Navy proposal for an aircraft carrier concept with a length of 1,310 feet and a displacement of 500,000 tons full load at a cost of $828 million in 1976 dollars.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Project Habakkuk could be considered an early proposal for an "ultracarrier".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Several systems of identification symbol for aircraft carriers and related types of ship have been used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] These include the pennant numbers used by the Royal Navy, Commonwealth countries, and Europe, along with the hull classification symbols used by the US and Canada.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Two months later, on 18 January 1911, Ely landed his Curtiss Pusher airplane on a platform on the armored cruiser USS *Pennsylvania* anchored in San Francisco Bay.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seaplane tender support ships came next, with the French *Foudre* of 1911.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Early in World War I, the Imperial Japanese Navy ship *Wakamiya* conducted the world's first carrier-launched air raid: on 6 September 1914, the *Wakamiya* used its crane to lower Farman seaplanes into the water.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Wakamiya* attacked the Austro-Hungarian cruiser SMS *Kaiserin Elisabeth* and the Imperial German gunboat *Jaguar* in Jiaozhou Bay off Qingdao; neither was hit.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first attack using an air-launched torpedo occurred on 2 August, when a torpedo was fired by Flight Commander Charles Edmonds from a Short Type 184 seaplane, launched from the seaplane carrier HMS *Ben-my-Chree*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first carrier-launched airstrike was the Tondern raid in July 1918.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Seven Sopwith Camels were launched from the battlecruiser HMS *Furious*, which had been completed as a carrier by replacing her planned forward turret with a flight deck and hangar prior to commissioning.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Camels attacked and damaged the German airbase at Tondern, Germany (modern day Tønder, Denmark), and destroyed two zeppelin airships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The first landing of an airplane on a moving ship was by Squadron Commander Edwin Harris Dunning, when he landed his Sopwith Pup on HMS *Furious* in Scapa Flow, Orkney, on 2 August 1917.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Landing on the forward flight deck required the pilot to approach round the ship's superstructure, a difficult and dangerous manoeuver, and Dunning was later killed when his airplane was thrown overboard while attempting another landing on *Furious*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] HMS *Furious* was modified again when her rear turret was removed and another flight deck added over a second hangar for landing aircraft over the stern.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Her funnel and superstructure remained intact, however, and turbulence from the funnel and superstructure was severe enough that only three landing attempts were successful before further attempts were forbidden.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This experience prompted the development of vessels with a flush deck and produced the first large fleet ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] In 1918, HMS *Argus* became the world's first carrier capable of launching and recovering naval aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] As a result of the Washington Naval Treaty of 1922, which limited the construction of new heavy surface combat ships, most early aircraft carriers were conversions of ships that were laid down (or had served) as different ship types: cargo ships, cruisers, battlecruisers, or battleships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] These conversions gave rise to the USS *Langley* in 1922, the US *Lexington*-class aircraft carriers (1927), Japanese *Akagi* and *Kaga*, and British *Courageous* class (of which *Furious* was one).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Specialist carrier evolution was well underway, with several navies ordering and building warships that were purposefully designed to function as aircraft carriers by the mid-1920s.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This resulted in the commissioning of ships such as the Japanese *Hōshō* (1922), HMS *Hermes* (1924, although laid down in 1918 before *Hōshō*), and *Béarn* (1927).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] During World War II, these ships would become known as fleet carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The aircraft carrier dramatically changed naval warfare in World War II, because air power was becoming a significant factor in warfare.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The advent of aircraft as focal weapons was driven by the superior range, flexibility, and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] They had greater range and precision than naval guns, making them highly effective.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The versatility of the carrier was demonstrated in November 1940, when HMS *Illustrious* launched a long-range strike on the Italian fleet at their base in Taranto, signalling the beginning of the effective and highly mobile aircraft strikes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This operation in the shallow water harbor incapacitated three of the six anchored battleships at a cost of two torpedo bombers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] World War II in the Pacific Ocean involved clashes between aircraft carrier fleets.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The Japanese surprise attack on the American Pacific fleet at Pearl Harbor naval and air bases on Sunday, 7 December 1941, was a clear illustration of the power projection capability afforded by a large force of modern carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Concentrating six carriers in a single unit turned naval history about, as no other nation had fielded anything comparable.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] In the "Doolittle Raid", on 18 April 1942, the US Navy carrier USS *Hornet* sailed to within 650 nautical miles (1,200 km) of Japan and launched 16 B-25 Mitchell medium bombers from her deck in a demonstrative retaliatory strike on the mainland, including the capital, Tokyo.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] However, the vulnerability of carriers compared to traditional capital ships was illustrated by the sinking of HMS *Glorious* by German battleships during the Norwegian campaign in 1940.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This new-found importance of naval aviation forced nations to create a number of carriers, in efforts to provide air superiority cover for every major fleet to ward off enemy aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This extensive usage led to the development and construction of 'light' carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Escort aircraft carriers, such as USS *Bogue*, were sometimes purpose-built but most were converted from merchant ships as a stop-gap measure to provide anti-submarine air support for convoys and amphibious invasions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following this concept, light aircraft carriers built by the US, such as USS *Independence* (commissioned in 1943), represented a larger, more "militarized" version of the escort carrier.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although with similar complement to escort carriers, they had the advantage of speed from their converted cruiser hulls.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The UK 1942 Design Light Fleet Carrier was designed for building quickly by civilian shipyards and with an expected service life of about 3 years.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] They served the Royal Navy during the war, and the hull design was chosen for nearly all aircraft carrier equipped navies after the war, until the 1980s.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Emergencies also spurred the creation or conversion of highly unconventional aircraft carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] CAM ships were cargo-carrying merchant ships that could launch (but not retrieve) a single fighter aircraft from a catapult to defend the convoy from long range land-based German aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Noteworthy converted carriers were also USS *Sable* (IX-81) and USS *Wolverine* (IX-64) that both operated on the Great Lakes for training duties and were converted from paddle steamers, making them the only aircraft carriers with this type of propulsion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before World War II, international naval treaties of 1922, 1930, and 1936 limited the size of capital ships, including carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since World War II, aircraft carrier designs have increased in size to accommodate a steady increase in aircraft size.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The large, modern *Nimitz* class of US Navy carriers has a displacement nearly four times that of the World War II–era USS *Enterprise*, yet its complement of aircraft is roughly the same—a consequence of the steadily increasing size and weight of individual military aircraft over the years.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Today's aircraft carriers are so expensive that some nations which operate them risk significant economic and military impact if a carrier is lost.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Modern navies that operate such aircraft carriers treat them as capital ships of fleets, a role previously held by the galleons, ships-of-the-line and battleships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This change took place during World War II in response to air power becoming a significant factor in warfare, driven by the superior range, flexibility and effectiveness of carrier-launched aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Following the war, carrier operations continued to increase in size and importance, and along with, carrier designs also increased in size and ability.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some of these larger carriers, dubbed by the media as "supercarriers", displacing 75,000 tons or greater, have become the pinnacle of carrier development.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Some are powered by nuclear reactors and form the core of a fleet designed to operate far from home.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Amphibious assault ships, such as the *Wasp* and *Mistral* classes, serve the purpose of carrying and landing Marines, and operate a large contingent of helicopters for that purpose.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Also known as "commando carriers" or "helicopter carriers", many have the capability to operate VSTOL aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The threatening role of aircraft carriers has a place in modern asymmetric warfare, like the gunboat diplomacy of the past.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers also facilitate quick and precise projections of overwhelming military power into such local and regional conflicts.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Lacking the firepower of other warships, carriers by themselves are considered vulnerable to attack by other ships, aircraft, submarines, or missiles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The resulting group of ships is often termed a carrier strike group, battle group, carrier group, or carrier battle group.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] There is a view among some military pundits that modern anti-ship weapons systems, such as torpedoes and missiles, or even ballistic missiles with nuclear warheads have made aircraft carriers and carrier groups too vulnerable for modern combat.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers are large and long ships, although there is a high degree of variation depending on their intended role and aircraft complement.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The size of the carrier has varied over history and among navies, to cater to the various roles that global climates have demanded from naval aviation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Regardless of size, the ship itself must house their complement of aircraft, with space for launching, storing, and maintaining them.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Space is also required for the large crew, supplies (food, munitions, fuel, engineering parts), and propulsion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] US and French aircraft carriers are notable for having nuclear reactors powering their systems and propulsion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The top of the carrier is the flight deck, where aircraft are launched and recovered.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the starboard side of this is the island, where ship navigation from the bridge and air traffic control from flyco are controlled and (in non-nuclear powered vessels), provides the location of the ship's funnel(s).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *Queen Elizabeth*-class has two island structures; the forward island contains the navigation bridge, while the aft structure houses flyco.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The constraints of constructing a flight deck strongly affect the role of a given carrier, as they influence the weight, type, and configuration of the aircraft that may be launched.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, assisted launch mechanisms are used primarily for heavy aircraft, especially those loaded with air-to-ground weapons.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR is most commonly used on US Navy fleet carriers as it allows the deployment of heavy jets with full load-outs, especially on ground-attack missions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] STOVL is used by other navies because it is cheaper to operate and still provides good deployment capability for fighter aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Due to the busy nature of the flight deck, only 20 or so aircraft may be on it at any one time.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] A hangar storage several decks below the flight deck is where most aircraft are kept, and aircraft are taken from the lower storage decks to the flight deck through the use of an elevator.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The hangar is usually quite large and can take up several decks of vertical space.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Munitions are commonly stored on the lower decks because they are highly explosive.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Usually this is below the waterline so that the area can be flooded in case of emergency.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] As "runways at sea", aircraft carriers have a flat-top flight deck, which launches and recovers aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft launch forward, into the wind, and are recovered from astern.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Creating such a surface at sea poses constraints on the carrier.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the size of the vessel is a fundamental limitation on runway length.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This affects take-off procedure, as a shorter runway length of the deck requires that aircraft accelerate more quickly to gain lift.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This either requires a thrust boost, a vertical component to its velocity, or a reduced take-off load (to lower mass).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The differing types of deck configuration, as above, influence the structure of the flight deck.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The form of launch assistance a carrier provides is strongly related to the types of aircraft embarked and the design of the carrier itself.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are two main philosophies to keep the deck short: add thrust to the aircraft, such as using a Catapult Assisted Take-Off (CATO-); and changing the direction of the airplanes' thrust, as in Vertical and/or Short Take-Off (V/STO-).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] On the recovery side of the flight deck, the adaptation to the aircraft load-out is mirrored.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Non-VTOL or conventional aircraft cannot decelerate on their own, and almost all carriers using them must have arrested-recovery systems (-BAR, e.g.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] CATOBAR or STOBAR) to recover their aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Aircraft that are landing extend a tailhook that catches on arrestor wires stretched across the deck to bring themselves to a stop in a short distance.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] If the aircraft are VTOL-capable or helicopters, they do not need to decelerate and hence there is no such need.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The arrested-recovery system has used an angled deck since the 1950s because, in case the aircraft does not catch the arresting wire, the short deck allows easier take off by reducing the number of objects between the aircraft and the end of the runway.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] It also has the advantage of separating the recovery operation area from the launch area.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Helicopters and aircraft capable of vertical or short take-off and landing (V/STOL) usually recover by coming abreast of the carrier on the port side and then using their hover capability to move over the flight deck and land vertically without the need for arresting gear.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carriers steam at speed, up to 35 knots (65 km/h; 40 mph) into the wind during flight deck operations to increase wind speed over the deck to a safe minimum.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This increase in effective wind speed provides a higher launch airspeed for aircraft at the end of the catapult stroke or ski-jump, as well as making recovery safer by reducing the difference between the relative speeds of the aircraft and ship.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Since the early 1950s on conventional carriers it has been the practice to recover aircraft at an angle to port of the axial line of the ship.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The primary function of this angled deck is to allow aircraft that miss the arresting wires, referred to as a bolter, to become airborne again without the risk of hitting aircraft parked forward.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The angled deck allows the installation of one or two "waist" catapults in addition to the two bow cats.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] An angled deck also improves launch and recovery cycle flexibility with the option of simultaneous launching and recovery of aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Conventional ("tailhook") aircraft rely upon a landing signal officer (LSO, radio call sign 'paddles') to monitor the aircraft's approach, visually gauge glideslope, attitude, and airspeed, and transmit that data to the pilot.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Before the angled deck emerged in the 1950s, LSOs used colored paddles to signal corrections to the pilot (hence the nickname).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] From the late 1950s onward, visual landing aids such as the optical landing system have provided information on proper glide slope, but LSOs still transmit voice calls to approaching pilots by radio.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Key personnel involved in the flight deck include the shooters, the handler, and the air boss.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Shooters are naval aviators or naval flight officers and are responsible for launching aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The handler works just inside the island from the flight deck and is responsible for the movement of aircraft before launching and after recovery.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The captain of the ship spends most of his time one level below primary on the Navigation Bridge.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Below this is the Flag Bridge, designated for the embarked admiral and his staff.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] To facilitate working on the flight deck of a US aircraft carrier, the sailors wear colored shirts that designate their responsibilities.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] There are at least seven different colors worn by flight deck personnel for modern United States Navy carrier air operations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Carrier operations of other nations use similar color schemes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The superstructure of a carrier (such as the bridge, flight control tower) are concentrated in a relatively small area called an *island*, a feature pioneered on HMS *Hermes* in 1923.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] While the island is usually built on the starboard side of the flight deck, the Japanese aircraft carriers *Akagi* and *Hiryū* had their islands built on the port side.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Very few carriers have been designed or built without an island.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] The *flush deck* configuration proved to have significant drawbacks, primary of which was management of the exhaust from the power plant.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Fumes coming across the deck were a major issue in USS *Langley*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] In addition, lack of an island meant difficulties managing the flight deck, performing air traffic control, a lack of radar housing placements and problems with navigating and controlling the ship itself.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another deck structure that can be seen is a ski-jump ramp at the forward end of the flight deck.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This was first developed to help launch short take off vertical landing (STOVL) aircraft take off at far higher weights than is possible with a vertical or rolling takeoff on flat decks.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Originally developed by the Royal Navy, it since has been adopted by many navies for smaller carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski-jump ramp works by converting some of the forward rolling movement of the aircraft into vertical velocity and is sometimes combined with the aiming of jet thrust partly downward.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] This allows heavily loaded and fueled aircraft a few more precious seconds to attain sufficient air velocity and lift to sustain normal flight.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Without a ski-jump, launching fully-loaded and fueled aircraft such as the Harrier would not be possible on a smaller flat deck ship before either stalling out or crashing directly into the sea.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Although STOVL aircraft are capable of taking off vertically from a spot on the deck, using the ramp and a running start is far more fuel efficient and permits a heavier launch weight.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] As catapults are unnecessary, carriers with this arrangement reduce weight, complexity, and space needed for complex steam or electromagnetic launching equipment.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Vertical landing aircraft also remove the need for arresting cables and related hardware.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Russian, Chinese, and Indian carriers include a ski-jump ramp for launching lightly loaded conventional fighter aircraft but recover using traditional carrier arresting cables and a tailhook on their aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] For example, the Russian Sukhoi Su-33 is only able to launch from the carrier *Admiral Kuznetsov* with a minimal armament and fuel load.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] Another disadvantage is on mixed flight deck operations where helicopters are also present, such as on a US landing helicopter dock or landing helicopter assault amphibious assault ship.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p01] A ski jump is not included as this would eliminate one or more helicopter landing areas; this flat deck limits the loading of Harriers but is somewhat mitigated by the longer rolling start provided by a long flight deck compared to many STOVL carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United States operates 11 nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carriers, with a total combined deck space over twice that of all other nations combined as of 2016.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] China operates one catapult-assisted aircraft carrier and two ski-jump carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The United Kingdom and India each currently operate two ski-jump aircraft carriers, and France operates one nuclear-powered, catapult-assisted carrier.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Russia deploys one ski-jump carrier, although it has not been operational since 2017.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the US operates nine large amphibious assault ships with the capability to launch vertical/short takeoff and landing (V/STOL) aircraft, and China operates four amphibious assault ships of a similar size as helicopter carriers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Italy operates two light V/STOL carriers, and both Spain and Iran operate one V/STOL aircraft-carrying assault ship.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Helicopter carriers are also operated by Japan (4, two converting to operate V/STOL fighters) France (3), Australia (2), Egypt (2), South Korea (2), Thailand (1), Brazil (1) and Iran (1).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Future aircraft carriers are under construction or planned by China, France, India, Italy, Russia, South Korea, and the US.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Royal Australian Navy operates two *Canberra*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two-ship class, based on the Spanish vessel *Juan Carlos I* and built by Navantia and BAE Systems Australia, represents the largest ships ever built for the Royal Australian Navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMAS *Canberra* underwent sea trials in late 2013 and was commissioned in 2014.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Her sister ship, HMAS *Adelaide*, was commissioned in December 2015.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Australian ships retain the ski-ramp from the *Juan Carlos I* design, although the RAN has not acquired carrier-based fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2017, the Brazilian Navy confirmed the purchase of HMS *Ocean* for (GBP) £84.6 million (equivalent to R$359.5M and US$113.2M) and renamed her *Atlântico*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship was decommissioned from Royal Navy service in March 2018.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Brazilian Navy commissioned the carrier on 29 June 2018 in the United Kingdom.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] After undertaking a period of maintenance in the UK, the ship travelled to its new home port, Rio de Janeiro Navy Arsenal (AMRJ) to be fully operational by 2020.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Before leaving HMNB Devonport for her new homeport in Rio's AMRJ, *Atlântico* underwent operational sea training under the Royal Navy's Flag Officer Sea Training (FOST) program.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] China has had a long-term plan to operate six large aircraft carriers with two carriers per fleet.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is planning a class of eight LHD vessels, the Type 075 (NATO reporting name Yushen-class landing helicopter assault).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] This is a class of amphibious assault ship under construction by the Hudong–Zhonghua Shipbuilding company.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first ship was commissioned in April 2021.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] China is also planning a modified class of the same concept, the Type 076 landing helicopter dock, that will be equipped with an electromagnetic catapult system and will likely support launching unmanned combat aerial vehicles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Egypt signed a contract with French shipbuilder DCNS to buy two *Mistral*-class helicopter carriers for approximately 950 million euros.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The two ships were originally to be sold to Russia, but the deal was cancelled by France due to the Russian invasion of Ukraine in 2014.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 2 June 2016, Egypt received the first of two helicopter carriers acquired in October 2015, the landing helicopter dock *Gamal Abdel Nasser*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The flag transfer ceremony took place in the presence of Egyptian and French Navies' chiefs of staff, chairman and chief executive officers of both DCNS and STX France, and senior Egyptian and French officials.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 16 September 2016, DCNS delivered the second of two helicopter carriers, the landing helicopter dock *Anwar El Sadat* which also participated in a joint military exercise with the French Navy before arriving at her home port of Alexandria.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The French Navy operates the 42,000-tonne nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, *Charles de Gaulle*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Commissioned in 2001, she is the flagship of the French Navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship carries a complement of Dassault Rafale M and E-2C Hawkeye aircraft, EC725 Caracal and AS532 Cougar helicopters for combat search and rescue, as well as modern electronics and Aster missiles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] She is a CATOBAR-type carrier that uses two 75 m C13-3 steam catapults of a shorter version of the catapult system installed on the US *Nimitz*-class carriers, one catapult at the bow and one across the front of the landing area.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In addition, the French Navy operates three *Mistral*-class landing helicopter docks.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In October 2018, the French Ministry of Defence began an 18-month €40 million study for the replacement of the French aircraft carrier *Charles de Gaulle* sometime after 2030.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, President Macron announced that construction of the next generation carrier would begin in around 2025 with sea trials to start in about 2036.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is planned to have a displacement of around 75,000 tons and to carry about 32 next-generation fighters, two to three E-2D Advanced Hawkeyes and a yet-to-be-determined number of unmanned carrier air vehicles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has plans for a third carrier, INS *Vishal*, also known as *Indigenous Aircraft Carrier 2 (IAC-2)* with a displacement of over 65,000 tonnes and is planned with a CATOBAR system to launch and recover heavier aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] India has also issued a request for information (RFI) to procure four Landing helicopter dock displacing 30,000–40,000 tons with a capacity to operate 12 medium lift special ops and two heavy lift helicopters and troops for amphibious operations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] On February 6, 2025, the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC) accepted the IRIS *Shahid Bagheri*, a 41,978-tonne drone UAV carrier converted from a container ship.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] was launched August 2013 and commissioned March 2015.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] the Japanese defense ministry's position is "We are not creating carrier air wings or carrier air squadrons" similar to the US Navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] from land bases; according to the 2020 Japanese Defense Ministry white paper the STOVL model was chosen for the JASDF due the lack of appropriately long runways to support air superiority capability across all of Japanese airspace.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] ships "for cooperation and advice on how to operate the fighter on the deck of the modified ships".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] , marking 75 years since fixed-wing aircraft operated from a Japanese carrier.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Portuguese Navy plans, for the second half of 2026, to receive the NRP *D.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] João II*, a platform ship capable of operating aerial, surface and underwater drones, medium helicopters (Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk) and heavy helicopters (EH101 Merlin) helicopters of the Portuguese Air Force.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] One STOBAR carrier: *Admiral Flota Sovetskogo Soyuza Kuznetsov*: 55,000-tonne *Kuznetsov*-class STOBAR aircraft carrier.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Launched in 1985 as *Tbilisi*, renamed and operational from 1995.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Without catapults she can launch and recover lightly fueled naval fighters for air defense or anti-ship missions but not heavy conventional bombing strikes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Officially designated an aircraft carrying cruiser, she is unique in carrying a heavy cruiser's complement of defensive weapons and large P-700 Granit offensive missiles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The P-700 systems will be removed in the coming refit to enlarge her below decks aviation facilities as well as upgrading her defensive systems.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The ship has been out of service and in repairs since 2018.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The most recent projection stated that repairs would be completed and the ship transferred back to the Russian Navy sometime in 2024, however this projection has not been met as of July 2025, and no updates have been provided.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Russian government has been considering the potential replacement of *Admiral Kuznetsov* for some time and has considered the Shtorm-class aircraft carrier as a possible option.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] This carrier will be a hybrid of CATOBAR and STOBAR, given the fact that she uses both systems of launching aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier is expected to cost between $1.8 billion and $5.63 billion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2020, the project had not yet been approved and, given the financial costs, it was unclear whether it would be made a priority over other elements of Russian naval modernization.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] A class of 2 LHD, Project 23900 is planned and an official keel laying ceremony for the project happened on 20 July 2020.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two *Dokdo*-class 18,860-tonne full deck amphibious assault ships with hospital and well deck and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] South Korea had set tentative plans for procuring two light aircraft carriers by 2033, which would help make the ROKN a blue water navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In December 2020, details of South Korea's planned carrier program (CVX) were finalized.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] A vessel of about 40,000 tons is envisaged carrying about 20 F-35B fighters as well as future maritime attack helicopters.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Service entry had been anticipated in the early 2030s.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In 2025 the program was cancelled and replaced with a drone carrier program.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] One offshore helicopter support ship: HTMS *Chakri Naruebet* helicopter carrier: 11,400-tonne STOVL carrier based on Spanish *Príncipe de Asturias* design.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AV-8S Matador/Harrier STOVL fighter wing, mostly inoperable by 1999, was retired from service without replacement in 2006.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] As of 2010, the ship is used for helicopter operations and for disaster relief.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* is a 27,079-tonne amphibious assault ship (LHD) (outfitted as drone carrier) of the Turkish Navy that can be configured as a 24,660-tonne V/STOL aircraft carrier.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Construction began on 30 April 2016 by Sedef Shipbuilding Inc. at their Istanbul shipyard.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] TCG *Anadolu* was commissioned with a ceremony on 10 April 2023.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of a sister ship, to be named TCG *Trakya*, is currently being planned by the Turkish Navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Sikorsky S-70B Seahawk and the Bell AH-1 SuperCobra are the two main types of helicopters used on TCG *Anadolu*, with the occasional use of CH-47F Chinook helicopters of the Turkish Army during military exercises and operations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The AH-1W Super Cobras will eventually be complemented and replaced by the TAI T929 ATAK 2.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The jet-powered, low-observable drone Bayraktar MIUS Kızılelma and the MALE UAV Bayraktar TB3 are two UCAVs that are specifically designed and manufactured by Baykar Technologies to be used on TCG *Anadolu*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The maiden flight of TAI Anka-3 (also part of Project MIUS), a jet-powered, flying wing type UCAV with stealth technology, was successfully completed on 28 December 2023.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 19 November 2024, Baykar Bayraktar TB3 UCAV successfully took-off from the flight deck of TCG *Anadolu* and landed on the ship.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] It was the first time a fixed-wing unmanned aircraft of this size and class had successfully landed on a short-runway landing helicopter dock, without the use of an arresting gear.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 3 January 2024, the Turkish government approved the plan for the design and construction of a larger aircraft carrier, named the *MUGEM*-class.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] On 15 February 2024, the Design and Projects Office of the Turkish Navy announced that it will be a STOBAR aircraft carrier with an overall length of 285 metres (935 ft), beam of 72 metres (236 ft), draught of 10.1 metres (33 ft), and displacement of 60,000 tons.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is to have a combined diesel–electric and gas (CODLAG) propulsion system and a maximum speed of more than 25 knots (29 mph; 46 km/h).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The construction of the first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier began on 2 January 2025.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first *MUGEM*-class aircraft carrier is being built at the Istanbul Naval Shipyard.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Two 80,600-tonne (est. full load) *Queen Elizabeth*-class STOVL carriers which operate the F-35 Lightning II.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] HMS *Queen Elizabeth* was commissioned in December 2017 and HMS *Prince of Wales* in December 2019.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The current US fleet of *Nimitz*-class carriers will be followed into service (and in some cases replaced) by the *Gerald R.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] It is expected that the ships will be more automated in an effort to reduce the amount of funding required to maintain and operate the vessels.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The main new features are implementation of Electromagnetic Aircraft Launch System (EMALS) (which replaces the old steam catapults) and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In terms of future carrier developments, Congress has discussed the possibility of accelerating the phasing-out of one or more *Nimitz*-class carriers, postponing or canceling the procurement of CVN-81 and CVN-82, or modifying the purchase contract.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Following the deactivation of USS *Enterprise* in December 2012, the US fleet comprised 10 fleet carriers, but that number increased back to 11 with the commissioning of *Gerald R.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The House Armed Services Seapower subcommittee on 24 July 2007, recommended seven or eight new carriers (one every four years).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] However, the debate has deepened over budgeting for the $12–14.5 billion (plus $12 billion for development and research) for the 100,000-tonne *Gerald R.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Ford*-class carrier (estimated service 2017) compared to the smaller $2 billion 45,000-tonne *America*-class amphibious assault ships, which are able to deploy squadrons of F-35Bs.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The first of this class, USS *America*, is now in active service with another, USS *Tripoli*, and 9 more are planned.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In a report to Congress in February 2018, the Navy stated it intends to maintain a "12 CVN force" as part of its 30-year acquisition plan.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] A few aircraft carriers have been preserved as museum ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently portrayed in a number of Hollywood films including *Midway* (2019) and the carrier USS *Nimitz* is centrally featured in the science fiction film *The Final Countdown* (1980).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The original film version about the Battle at Midway was made in England and titled *Midway* (1976).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Aircraft carriers are prominently featured in both *Top Gun* and *Top Gun: Maverick* as providing the launch sites and mission operations support for the fighter operations seen in both films.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The Japanese aircraft carriers involved in the attack on Pearl Harbor are featured in the 1970 film *Tora!
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] Tora!* as well as the more recent film from 2001 *Pearl Harbor*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The carrier USS *Ronald Reagan* makes a cameo appearance at the end of the 2012 science fiction film *Battleship*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] In the 2025 film *Mission: Impossible – The Final Reckoning*, the aircraft carrier USS *George Bush* is featured as delivering its special agent to a submarine rendezvous with the nuclear-powered USS *Ohio* in the Bering Straits by Alaska.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/aircraft-carrier-p02] The 50-minute documentary titled *City of Steel: Carrier* was released by the Discovery Channel in 2000 covering the final months of building and inspecting the USS *Harry Truman* through its commissioning by President Bill Clinton.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/asme] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] A **boiler** is a closed vessel in which fluid (generally water) is heated.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The heated or vaporized fluid exits the boiler for use in various processes or heating applications, including water heating, central heating, boiler-based power generation, cooking, and sanitation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In a fossil fuel power plant using a steam cycle for power generation, the primary heat source will be combustion of coal, oil, or natural gas.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In some cases byproduct fuel such as the carbon monoxide rich offgasses of a coke battery can be burned to heat a boiler; biofuels such as bagasse, where economically available, can also be used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In a nuclear power plant, boilers called steam generators are heated by the heat produced by nuclear fission.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Where a large volume of hot gas is available from some process, a heat recovery steam generator or recovery boiler can use the heat to produce steam, with little or no extra fuel consumed; such a configuration is common in a combined cycle power plant where a gas turbine and a steam boiler are used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In all cases the combustion product waste gases are separate from the working fluid of the steam cycle, making these systems examples of external combustion engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The pressure vessel of a boiler is usually made of steel (or alloy steel), or historically of wrought iron.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Stainless steel, especially of the austenitic types, is not used in wetted parts of boilers due to corrosion and stress corrosion cracking.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] However, ferritic stainless steel is often used in superheater sections that will not be exposed to boiling water, and electrically heated stainless steel shell boilers are allowed under the European "Pressure Equipment Directive" for production of steam for sterilizers and disinfectors.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In live steam models, copper or brass is often used because it is more easily fabricated in smaller size boilers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] For much of the Victorian "age of steam", the only material used for boilermaking was the highest grade of wrought iron, with assembly by riveting.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] This iron was often obtained from specialist ironworks, such as those in the Cleator Moor (UK) area, noted for the high quality of their rolled plate, which was especially suitable for use in critical applications such as high-pressure boilers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In the 20th century, design practice moved towards the use of steel, with welded construction, which is stronger and cheaper, and can be fabricated more quickly and with less labour.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Wrought iron boilers corrode far more slowly than their modern-day steel counterparts, and are less susceptible to localized pitting and stress-corrosion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] That makes the longevity of older wrought-iron boilers far superior to that of welded steel boilers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Cast iron may be used for the heating vessel of domestic water heaters.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Although such heaters are usually termed "boilers" in some countries, their purpose is usually to produce hot water, not steam, and so they run at low pressure and try to avoid boiling.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The brittleness of cast iron makes it impractical for high-pressure steam boilers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The source of heat for a boiler is combustion of any of several fuels, such as wood, coal, oil, or natural gas.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Electric steam boilers use resistance- or immersion-type heating elements.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Nuclear fission is also used as a heat source for generating steam, either directly (BWR) or, in most cases, in specialised heat exchangers called "steam generators" (PWR).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Heat recovery steam generators (HRSGs) use the heat rejected from other processes such as gas turbine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Direct method of boiler efficiency test is more usable or more common.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] A primitive "kettle" where a fire heats a partially filled water container from below.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] 18th-century Haycock boilers generally produced and stored large volumes of very low-pressure steam, often hardly above that of the atmosphere.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] These could burn wood or most often, coal.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] This is the type of boiler used in nearly all steam locomotives.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Fire-tube boilers usually have a comparatively low rate of steam production, but high steam storage capacity.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Fire-tube boilers mostly burn solid fuels, but are readily adaptable to those of the liquid or gas variety.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Fire-tube boilers may also be referred to as "scotch-marine" or "marine" type boilers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In this type, tubes filled with water are arranged inside a furnace in a number of possible configurations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Often the water tubes connect large drums, the lower ones containing water and the upper ones steam and water; in other cases, such as a mono-tube boiler, water is circulated by a pump through a succession of coils.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] This type generally gives high steam production rates, but less storage capacity than fire-tube boilers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Water tube boilers can be designed to exploit any heat source and are generally preferred in high-pressure applications since the high-pressure water/steam is contained within small diameter pipes which can withstand the pressure with a thinner wall.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] These boilers are commonly constructed in place, roughly square in shape, and can be multiple stories tall.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] A flash boiler is a specialized type of water-tube boiler in which tubes are close together and water is pumped through them.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] A flash boiler differs from the type of mono-tube steam generator in which the tube is permanently filled with water.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Flash boilers had some use in automobiles in the 19th century and this use continued into the early 20th century.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The gases then pass through a conventional firetube boiler.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] but have met with little success in other countries.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In a cast iron sectional boiler, sometimes called a "pork chop boiler" the water is contained inside cast iron sections.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] These sections are assembled on site to create the finished boiler.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] To define and secure boilers safely, some professional specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] For instance, the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code is a standard providing a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the boilers and other pressure vessels with safety, security and design standards.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Historically, boilers were a source of many serious injuries and property destruction due to poorly understood engineering principles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Thin and brittle metal shells can rupture, while poorly welded or riveted seams could open up, leading to a violent eruption of the pressurized steam.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] When water is converted to steam it expands to over 1,000 times its original volume and travels down steam pipes at over 100 kilometres per hour (62 mph).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Because of this, steam is an efficient method of moving energy and heat around a site from a central boiler house to where it is needed, but without the right boiler feedwater treatment, a steam-raising plant will suffer from scale formation and corrosion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] At best, this increases energy costs and can lead to poor quality steam, reduced efficiency, shorter plant life and unreliable operation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] At worst, it can lead to catastrophic failure and loss of life.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Collapsed or dislodged boiler tubes can also spray scalding-hot steam and smoke out of the air intake and firing chute, injuring the firemen who load the coal into the fire chamber.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Extremely large boilers providing hundreds of horsepower to operate factories can potentially demolish entire buildings.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] A boiler that has a loss of feed water and is permitted to boil dry can be extremely dangerous.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] If feed water is then sent into the empty boiler, the small cascade of incoming water instantly boils on contact with the superheated metal shell and leads to a violent explosion that cannot be controlled even by safety steam valves.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Draining of the boiler can also happen if a leak occurs in the steam supply lines that is larger than the make-up water supply could replace.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The *Hartford Loop* was invented in 1919 by the Hartford Steam Boiler Inspection and Insurance Company as a method to help prevent this condition from occurring, and thereby reduce their insurance claims.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] When water is boiled the result is saturated steam, also referred to as "wet steam." Saturated steam, while mostly consisting of water vapor, carries some unevaporated water in the form of droplets.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Saturated steam is useful for many purposes, such as cooking, heating and sanitation, but is not desirable when steam is expected to convey energy to machinery, such as a ship's propulsion system or the "motion" of a steam locomotive.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] This is because unavoidable temperature and/or pressure loss that occurs as steam travels from the boiler to the machinery will cause some condensation, resulting in liquid water being carried into the machinery.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The water entrained in the steam may damage turbine blades or in the case of a reciprocating steam engine, may cause serious mechanical damage due to hydrostatic lock.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Superheated steam boilers evaporate the water and then further heat the steam in a *superheater*, causing the discharged steam temperature to be substantially above the boiling temperature at the boiler's operating pressure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] As the resulting "dry steam" is much hotter than needed to stay in the vaporous state it will not contain any significant unevaporated water.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Also, higher steam pressure will be possible than with saturated steam, enabling the steam to carry more energy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Although superheating adds more energy to the steam in the form of heat there is no effect on pressure, which is determined by the rate at which steam is drawn from the boiler and the pressure settings of the safety valves.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The fuel consumption required to generate superheated steam is greater than that required to generate an equivalent volume of saturated steam.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] However, the overall energy efficiency of the steam plant (the combination of boiler, superheater, piping and machinery) generally will be improved enough to more than offset the increased fuel consumption.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Superheater operation is similar to that of the coils on an air conditioning unit, although for a different purpose.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The steam piping is directed through the flue gas path in the boiler furnace, an area in which the temperature is typically between 1,300 and 1,600 degrees Celsius (2,372 and 2,912 degrees Fahrenheit).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Some superheaters are radiant type, which as the name suggests, they absorb heat by radiation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Others are convection type, absorbing heat from a fluid.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Some are a combination of the two types.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Through either method, the extreme heat in the flue gas path will also heat the superheater steam piping and the steam within.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The design of any superheated steam plant presents several engineering challenges due to the high working temperatures and pressures.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] One consideration is the introduction of feedwater to the boiler.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The pump used to charge the boiler must be able to overcome the boiler's operating pressure, else water will not flow.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] As a superheated boiler is usually operated at high pressure, the corresponding feedwater pressure must be even higher, demanding a more robust pump design.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] High pressure, superheated steam can be extremely dangerous if it unintentionally escapes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] To give the reader some perspective, the steam plants used in many U.S.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Navy destroyers built during World War II operated at 600 psi (4,100 kPa; 41 bar) pressure and 850 degrees Fahrenheit (454 degrees Celsius) superheat.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Also, small leaks that are not visible at the point of leakage could be lethal if an individual were to step into the escaping steam's path.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Hence designers endeavor to give the steam-handling components of the system as much strength as possible to maintain integrity.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Special methods of coupling steam pipes together are used to prevent leaks, with very high pressure systems employing welded joints to avoid leakage problems with threaded or gasketed connections.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Supercritical steam generators are frequently used for the production of electric power.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] In contrast to a "subcritical boiler", a supercritical steam generator operates at such a high pressure (over 3,200 psi or 22 MPa) that the physical turbulence that characterizes boiling ceases to occur; the fluid is neither liquid nor gas but a supercritical fluid.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] There is no generation of steam bubbles within the water, because the pressure is above the critical pressure point at which steam bubbles can form.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] As the fluid expands through the turbine stages, its thermodynamic state drops below the critical point as it does work turning the turbine which turns the electrical generator from which power is ultimately extracted.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The fluid at that point may be a mix of steam and liquid droplets as it passes into the condenser.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] This results in slightly less fuel use and therefore less greenhouse gas production.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The term "boiler" should not be used for a supercritical pressure steam generator, as no "boiling" occurs in this device.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] A fuel-heated boiler must provide air to oxidize its fuel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Early boilers provided this stream of air, or *draught*, through the natural action of convection in a chimney connected to the exhaust of the combustion chamber.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Since the heated flue gas is less dense than the ambient air surrounding the boiler, the flue gas rises in the chimney, pulling denser, fresh air into the combustion chamber.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Most modern boilers depend on mechanical draught rather than natural draught.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] This is because natural draught is subject to outside air conditions and temperature of flue gases leaving the furnace, as well as the chimney height.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] All these factors make proper draught hard to attain and therefore make mechanical draught equipment much more reliable and economical.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Types of draught can also be divided into *induced draught*, where exhaust gases are pulled out of the boiler; *forced draught*, where fresh air is pushed into the boiler; and *balanced draught*, where both effects are employed.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Natural draught through the use of a chimney is a type of induced draught; mechanical draught can be induced, forced or balanced.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] There are two types of mechanical induced draught.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The first is through use of a steam jet.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The steam jet oriented in the direction of flue gas flow induces flue gases into the stack and allows for a greater flue gas velocity increasing the overall draught in the furnace.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] This method was common on steam driven locomotives which could not have tall chimneys.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The second method is by simply using an induced draught fan (ID fan) which removes flue gases from the furnace and forces the exhaust gas up the stack.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Almost all induced draught furnaces operate with a slightly negative pressure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Mechanical forced draught is provided by means of a fan forcing air into the combustion chamber.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Air is often passed through an air heater; which, as the name suggests, heats the air going into the furnace to increase the overall efficiency of the boiler.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Dampers are used to control the quantity of air admitted to the furnace.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Forced draught furnaces usually have a positive pressure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] Balanced draught is obtained through use of both induced and forced draught.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] This is more common with larger boilers where the flue gases have to travel a long distance through many boiler passes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/boiler] The induced draught fan works in conjunction with the forced draught fan allowing the furnace pressure to be maintained slightly below atmospheric.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] A **burn** is an injury to skin, or other tissues, caused by heat, electricity, chemicals, friction, or ionizing radiation (such as sunburn, caused by ultraviolet radiation).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Most burns are thermal burns caused by contact with heat from hot fluids (called scalding), solids, or fire.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns occur mainly in the home or the workplace.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the home, risks are associated with domestic kitchens, including stoves, flames, and hot liquids.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the workplace, risks are associated with fire and chemical and electric burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Alcoholism and smoking are other risk factors.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns can also occur as a result of self-harm or violence between people (assault).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns that affect only the superficial skin layers are known as superficial or **first-degree burns**.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] They appear red without blisters, and pain typically lasts around three days.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] When the injury extends into some of the underlying skin layer, it is a partial-thickness or **second-degree burn**.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Blisters are frequently present and they are often very painful.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Healing can require up to eight weeks and scarring may occur.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In a full-thickness or **third-degree burn**, the injury extends to all layers of the skin.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Often there is no pain and the burnt area is stiff.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Healing typically does not occur on its own.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] A **fourth-degree burn** additionally involves injury to deeper tissues, such as muscle, tendons, or bone.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The burn is often black and frequently leads to loss of the burned part.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Treatment depends on the severity of the burn.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Superficial burns may be managed with little more than simple pain medication, while major burns may require prolonged treatment in specialized burn centers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Cooling with tap water may help pain and decrease damage; however, prolonged cooling may result in low body temperature.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Partial-thickness burns may require cleaning with soap and water, followed by dressings.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] It is not clear how to manage blisters, but it is probably reasonable to leave them intact if small and drain them if large.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Full-thickness burns usually require surgical treatments, such as skin grafting.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Extensive burns often require large amounts of intravenous fluid, due to capillary fluid leakage and tissue swelling.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The most common complications of burns involve infection.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Tetanus toxoid should be given if not up to date.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In 2015, fire and heat resulted in 67 million injuries.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This resulted in about 2.9 million hospitalizations and 176,000 deaths.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Among women in much of the world, burns are most commonly related to the use of open cooking fires or unsafe cook stoves.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Among men, they are more likely a result of unsafe workplace conditions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Most deaths due to burns occur in the developing world, particularly in Southeast Asia.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While large burns can be fatal, treatments developed since 1960 have improved outcomes, especially in children and young adults.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the United States, approximately 96% of those admitted to a burn center survive their injuries.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The long-term outcome is related to the size of burn and the age of the person affected.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The characteristics of a burn depend upon its depth.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Superficial burns cause pain lasting two or three days, followed by peeling of the skin over the next few days.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Individuals with more severe burns may indicate discomfort or complain of feeling pressure rather than pain.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Full-thickness burns may be entirely insensitive to light touch or puncture.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While superficial burns are typically red in color, severe burns may be pink, white or black.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns around the mouth or singed hair inside the nose may indicate that burns to the airways have occurred, but these findings are not definitive.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] More worrisome signs include: shortness of breath, hoarseness, and stridor or wheezing.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Itchiness is common during the healing process, occurring in up to 90% of adults and nearly all children.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Numbness or tingling may persist for a prolonged period of time after an electrical injury.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns may also produce emotional and psychological distress.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns are caused by a variety of external sources classified as thermal (heat-related), chemical, electrical, and radiation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the United States, the most common causes of burns are: fire or flame (44%), scalds (33%), hot objects (9%), electricity (4%), and chemicals (3%).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Most (69%) burn injuries occur at home or at work (9%), and most are accidental, with 2% due to assault by another, and 1–2% resulting from a suicide attempt.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] These sources can cause inhalation injury to the airway and/or lungs, occurring in about 6%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burn injuries occur more commonly among the poor.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Smoking and alcoholism are other risk factors.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Fire-related burns are generally more common in colder climates.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Specific risk factors in the developing world include cooking with open fires or on the floor as well as developmental disabilities in children and chronic diseases in adults.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the United States, fire and hot liquids are the most common causes of burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Of house fires that result in death, smoking causes 25% and heating devices cause 22%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Almost half of injuries are due to efforts to fight a fire.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Scalding is caused by hot liquids or gases and most commonly occurs from exposure to hot drinks, high temperature tap water in baths or showers, hot cooking oil, or steam.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Scald injuries are most common in children under the age of five and, in the United States and Australia, this population makes up about two-thirds of all burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Contact with hot objects is the cause of about 20–30% of burns in children.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Generally, scalds are first- or second-degree burns, but third-degree burns may also result, especially with prolonged contact.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Fireworks are a common cause of burns during holiday seasons in many countries.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This is a particular risk for adolescent males.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the United States, for non-fatal burn injuries to children, white males under the age of 6 comprise most cases.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Thermal burns from grabbing/touching and spilling/splashing were the most common type of burn and mechanism, while the bodily areas most impacted were hands and fingers followed by head/neck.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Chemical burns can be caused by over 25,000 substances, most of which are either a strong base (55%) or a strong acid (26%).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Most chemical burn deaths are secondary to ingestion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Common agents include: sulfuric acid as found in toilet cleaners, sodium hypochlorite as found in bleach, and halogenated hydrocarbons as found in paint remover, among others.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Hydrofluoric acid can cause particularly deep burns that may not become symptomatic until some time after exposure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Formic acid may cause the breakdown of significant numbers of red blood cells.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Electrical burns or injuries are classified as high voltage (greater than or equal to 1000 volts), low voltage (less than 1000 volts), or as flash burns secondary to an electric arc.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The most common causes of electrical burns in children are electrical cords (60%) followed by electrical outlets (14%).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Lightning may also result in electrical burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Risk factors for being struck include involvement in outdoor activities such as mountain climbing, golf and field sports, and working outside.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Mortality from a lightning strike is about 10%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While electrical injuries primarily result in burns, they may also cause fractures or dislocations secondary to blunt force trauma or muscle contractions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In high voltage injuries, most damage may occur internally and thus the extent of the injury cannot be judged by examination of the skin alone.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Contact with either low voltage or high voltage may produce cardiac arrhythmias or cardiac arrest.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Radiation burns may be caused by protracted exposure to ultraviolet light (such as from the sun, tanning booths or arc welding) or from ionizing radiation (such as from radiation therapy, X-rays or radioactive fallout).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Sun exposure is the most common cause of radiation burns and the most common cause of superficial burns overall.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] There is significant variation in how easily people sunburn based on their skin type.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Skin effects from ionizing radiation depend on the amount of exposure to the area, with hair loss seen after 3 Gy, redness seen after 10 Gy, wet skin peeling after 20 Gy, and necrosis after 30 Gy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Redness, if it occurs, may not appear until some time after exposure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Radiation burns are treated the same as other burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Microwave burns occur via thermal heating caused by the microwaves.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While exposures as short as two seconds may cause injury, overall this is an uncommon occurrence.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In those hospitalized from scalds or fire burns, 3–10% are from assault.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Reasons include: child abuse, personal disputes, spousal abuse, elder abuse, and business disputes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] An immersion injury or immersion scald may indicate child abuse.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] It is created when an extremity, or sometimes the buttocks are held under the surface of hot water.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] It typically produces a sharp upper border and is often symmetrical, known as "sock burns", "glove burns", or "zebra stripes" - where folds have prevented certain areas from burning.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Deliberate cigarette burns are most often found on the face, or the back of the hands and feet.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Other high-risk signs of potential abuse include: circumferential burns, the absence of splash marks, a burn of uniform depth, and association with other signs of neglect or abuse.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Bride burning, a form of domestic violence, occurs in some cultures, such as India where women have been burned in revenge for what the husband or his family consider an inadequate dowry.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In Pakistan, acid burns represent 13% of intentional burns, and are frequently related to domestic violence.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Self-immolation (setting oneself on fire) is also used as a form of protest in various parts of the world.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] At temperatures greater than 44 °C (111 °F), proteins begin losing their three-dimensional shape and start breaking down.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Many of the direct health effects of a burn are caused by failure of the skin to perform its normal functions, which include: protection from bacteria, skin sensation, body temperature regulation, and prevention of evaporation of the body's water.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Disruption of these functions can lead to infection, loss of skin sensation, hypothermia, and hypovolemic shock via dehydration (i.e. water in the body evaporated away).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Disruption of cell membranes causes cells to lose potassium to the spaces outside the cell and to take up water and sodium.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In large burns (over 30% of the total body surface area), there is a significant inflammatory response.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This results in increased leakage of fluid from the capillaries, and subsequent tissue edema.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This causes overall blood volume loss, with the remaining blood suffering significant plasma loss, making the blood more concentrated.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Poor blood flow to organs like the kidneys and gastrointestinal tract may result in kidney failure and stomach ulcers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Increased levels of catecholamines and cortisol can cause a hypermetabolic state that can last for years.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This is associated with increased cardiac output, metabolism, a fast heart rate, and poor immune function.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns can be classified by depth, mechanism of injury, extent, and associated injuries.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The most commonly used classification is based on the depth of injury.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The depth of a burn is usually determined via examination, although a biopsy may also be used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] It may be difficult to accurately determine the depth of a burn on a single examination and repeated examinations over a few days may be necessary.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In those who have a headache or are dizzy and have a fire-related burn, carbon monoxide poisoning should be considered.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Cyanide poisoning should also be considered.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The size of a burn is measured as a percentage of total body surface area (TBSA) affected by partial thickness or full thickness burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] First-degree burns that are only red in color and are not blistering are not included in this estimation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Most burns (70%) involve less than 10% of the TBSA.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Unit of measuring burns is VSD as 10% TBSA is equal to 1VSD.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] There are a number of methods to determine the TBSA, including the Wallace rule of nines, Lund and Browder chart, and estimations based on a person's palm size.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The rule of nines is easy to remember but only accurate in people over 16 years of age.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] More accurate estimates can be made using Lund and Browder charts, which take into account the different proportions of body parts in adults and children.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The size of a person's handprint (including the palm and fingers) is approximately 1% of their TBSA.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] To determine the need for referral to a specialized burn unit, the American Burn Association devised a classification system.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Under this system, burns can be classified as major, moderate, and minor.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This is assessed based on a number of factors, including total body surface area affected, the involvement of specific anatomical zones, the age of the person, and associated injuries.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Minor burns can typically be managed at home, moderate burns are often managed in a hospital, and major burns are managed by a burn center.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Severe burn injury represents one of the most devastating forms of trauma.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Despite improvements in burn care, patients can be left to suffer for as many as three years post-injury.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Historically, about half of all burns were deemed preventable.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burn prevention programs have significantly decreased rates of serious burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Preventive measures include: limiting hot water temperatures, smoke alarms, sprinkler systems, proper construction of buildings, and fire-resistant clothing.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Experts recommend setting water heaters below 48.8 °C (119.8 °F).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Other measures to prevent scalds include using a thermometer to measure bath water temperatures, and splash guards on stoves.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While the effect of the regulation of fireworks is unclear, there is tentative evidence of benefit with recommendations including the limitation of the sale of fireworks to children.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Resuscitation begins with the assessment and stabilization of the person's airway, breathing and circulation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] If inhalation injury is suspected, early intubation may be required.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This is followed by care of the burn wound itself.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] People with extensive burns may be wrapped in clean sheets until they arrive at a hospital.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] As burn wounds are prone to infection, a tetanus booster shot should be given if an individual has not been immunized within the last five years.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the United States, 95% of burns that present to the emergency department are treated and discharged; 5% require hospital admission.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] With major burns, early feeding is important.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Protein intake should also be increased, and trace elements and vitamins are often required.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Hyperbaric oxygenation may be useful in addition to traditional treatments.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In those with poor tissue perfusion, boluses of isotonic crystalloid solution should be given.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In children with more than 10–20% TBSA (Total Body Surface Area) burns, and adults with more than 15% TBSA burns, formal fluid resuscitation and monitoring should follow.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This should be begun pre-hospital if possible in those with burns greater than 25% TBSA.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The Parkland formula can help determine the volume of intravenous fluids required over the first 24 hours.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The formula is based on the affected individual's TBSA and weight.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Half of the fluid is administered over the first 8 hours, and the remainder over the following 16 hours.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The time is calculated from when the burn occurred, and not from the time that fluid resuscitation began.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Children require additional maintenance fluid that includes glucose.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Additionally, those with inhalation injuries require more fluid.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While inadequate fluid resuscitation may cause problems, over-resuscitation can also be detrimental.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The formulas are only a guide, with infusions ideally tailored to a urinary output of >30 mL/h in adults or >1mL/kg in children and mean arterial pressure greater than 60 mmHg.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While lactated Ringer's solution is often used, there is no evidence that it is superior to normal saline.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Crystalloid fluids appear just as good as colloid fluids, and as colloids are more expensive they are not recommended.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] They are typically only recommended when the hemoglobin level falls below 60-80 g/L (6-8 g/dL) due to the associated risk of complications.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Intravenous catheters may be placed through burned skin if needed or intraosseous infusions may be used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Early cooling (within 30 minutes of the burn) reduces burn depth and pain, but care must be taken as over-cooling can result in hypothermia.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] It should be performed with cool water 10–25 °C (50.0–77.0 °F) and not ice water as the latter can cause further injury.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Chemical burns may require extensive irrigation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Cleaning with soap and water, removal of dead tissue, and application of dressings are important aspects of wound care.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] If intact blisters are present, it is not clear what should be done with them.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Some tentative evidence supports leaving them intact.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Second-degree burns should be re-evaluated after two days.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the management of first and second-degree burns, little quality evidence exists to determine which dressing type to use.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] It is reasonable to manage first-degree burns without dressings.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While topical antibiotics are often recommended, there is little evidence to support their use.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Silver sulfadiazine (a type of antibiotic) is not recommended as it potentially prolongs healing time.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] There is insufficient evidence to support the use of dressings containing silver or negative-pressure wound therapy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Silver sulfadiazine does not appear to differ from silver containing foam dressings with respect to healing.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns can be very painful and a number of different options may be used for pain management.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] These include simple analgesics (such as ibuprofen and acetaminophen) and opioids such as morphine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Benzodiazepines may be used in addition to analgesics to help with anxiety.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] During the healing process, antihistamines, massage, or transcutaneous nerve stimulation may be used to aid with itching.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Antihistamines, however, are only effective for this purpose in 20% of people.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] There is tentative evidence supporting the use of gabapentin and its use may be reasonable in those who do not improve with antihistamines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Intravenous lidocaine requires more study before it can be recommended for pain.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Intravenous antibiotics are recommended before surgery for those with extensive burns (>60% TBSA).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] As of 2008, guidelines do not recommend their general use due to concerns regarding antibiotic resistance and the increased risk of fungal infections.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Tentative evidence, however, shows that they may improve survival rates in those with large and severe burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Erythropoietin has not been found effective to prevent or treat anemia in burn cases.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In burns caused by hydrofluoric acid, calcium gluconate is a specific antidote and may be used intravenously and/or topically.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Recombinant human growth hormone (rhGH) in those with burns that involve more than 40% of their body appears to speed healing without affecting the risk of death.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The use of steroids is of unclear evidence.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Allogeneic cultured keratinocytes and dermal fibroblasts in murine collagen (Stratagraft) was approved for medical use in the United States in June 2021.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Wounds requiring surgical closure with skin grafts or flaps (typically anything more than a small full thickness burn) should be dealt with as early as possible.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Circumferential burns of the limbs or chest may need urgent surgical release of the skin, known as an escharotomy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This is done to treat or prevent problems with distal circulation, or ventilation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] It is uncertain if it is useful for neck or digit burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Fasciotomies may be required for electrical burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Skin grafts can involve temporary skin substitutes, derived from animal (human donor or pig) skin or synthesized.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] They are used to cover the wound as a dressing, preventing infection and fluid loss, but will eventually need to be removed.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Alternatively, human skin can be treated to be left on permanently without rejection.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] There is no evidence that the use of copper sulphate to visualise phosphorus particles for removal can help with wound healing due to phosphorus burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Meanwhile, absorption of copper sulphate into the blood circulation can be harmful.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Honey has been used since ancient times to aid wound healing and may be beneficial in first- and second-degree burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] There is moderate evidence that honey helps heal partial thickness burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The evidence for aloe vera is of poor quality.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] While it might be beneficial in reducing pain, and a review from 2007 found tentative evidence of improved healing times, a subsequent review from 2012 did not find improved healing over silver sulfadiazine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] A 2014 review found only three randomized controlled trials for the use of plants for burns, two for aloe vera and one for oatmeal.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The number of randomized control trials for aloe vera had increased to nine by 2024, when a review found a significant improvement in healing time but not pain relief.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] There is little evidence that vitamin E helps with keloids or scarring.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In low income countries, burns are treated up to one-third of the time with traditional medicine, which may include applications of eggs, mud, leaves or cow dung.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Surgical management is limited in some cases due to insufficient financial resources and availability.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] There are a number of other methods that may be used in addition to medications to reduce procedural pain and anxiety including virtual reality therapy, hypnosis, and behavioral approaches such as distraction techniques.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burn patients require support and care – both physiological and psychological.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Respiratory failure, sepsis, and multi-organ system failure are common in hospitalized burn patients.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] To prevent hypothermia and maintain normal body temperature, burn patients with over 20% of burn injuries should be kept in an environment with the temperature at or above 30 degree Celsius.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Metabolism in burn patients proceeds at a higher than normal speed due to the whole-body process and rapid fatty acid substrate cycles, which can be countered with an adequate supply of energy, nutrients, and antioxidants.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Enteral feeding a day after resuscitation is required to reduce risk of infection, recovery time, non-infectious complications, hospital stay, long-term damage, and mortality.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Controlling blood glucose levels can have an impact on liver function and survival.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Risk of thromboembolism is high and acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) that does not resolve with maximal ventilator use is also a common complication.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Scars are long-term after-effects of a burn injury.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The prognosis is worse in those with larger burns, those who are older, and females.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The presence of a smoke inhalation injury, other significant injuries such as long bone fractures, and serious co-morbidities (e.g. heart disease, diabetes, psychiatric illness, and suicidal intent) also influence prognosis.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] On average, of those admitted to burn centers in the United States, 4% die, with the outcome for individuals dependent on the extent of the burn injury.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] For example, admittees with burn areas less than 10% TBSA had a mortality rate of less than 1%, while admittees with over 90% TBSA had a mortality rate of 85%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In Afghanistan, people with more than 60% TBSA burns rarely survive.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The Baux score has historically been used to determine prognosis of major burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] However, with improved care, it is no longer very accurate.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The score is determined by adding the size of the burn (% TBSA) to the age of the person and taking that to be more or less equal to the risk of death.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Burns in 2013 resulted in 1.2 million years lived with disability and 12.3 million disability adjusted life years.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] A number of complications may occur, with infections being the most common.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In order of frequency, potential complications include: pneumonia, cellulitis, urinary tract infections and respiratory failure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Risk factors for infection include: burns of more than 30% TBSA, full-thickness burns, extremes of age (young or old), or burns involving the legs or perineum.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Pneumonia occurs particularly commonly in those with inhalation injuries.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Anemia secondary to full thickness burns of greater than 10% TBSA is common.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Electrical burns may lead to compartment syndrome or rhabdomyolysis due to muscle breakdown.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Blood clotting in the veins of the legs is estimated to occur in 6 to 25% of people.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The hypermetabolic state that may persist for years after a major burn can result in a decrease in bone density and a loss of muscle mass.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Keloids may form subsequent to a burn, particularly in those who are young and dark skinned.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Following a burn, children may have significant psychological trauma and experience post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Scarring may also result in a disturbance in body image.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] To treat hypertrophic scars (raised, tense, stiff and itchy scars) and limit their effect on physical function and everyday activities, silicone sheeting and compression garments are recommended.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the developing world, significant burns may result in social isolation, extreme poverty and child abandonment.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In 2015 fire and heat resulted in 67 million injuries.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This resulted in about 2.9 million hospitalizations and 238,000 dying.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This makes it the fourth leading cause of injuries after motor vehicle collisions, falls, and violence.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] About 90% of burns occur in the developing world.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This has been attributed partly to overcrowding and an unsafe cooking situation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Overall, nearly 60% of fatal burns occur in Southeast Asia with a rate of 11.6 per 100,000.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the developed world, adult males have twice the mortality as females from burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This is most probably due to their higher risk occupations and greater risk-taking activities.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In many countries in the developing world, however, females have twice the risk of males.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] This is often related to accidents in the kitchen or domestic violence.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In children, deaths from burns occur at more than ten times the rate in the developing than the developed world.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Overall, in children it is one of the top fifteen leading causes of death.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] From the 1980s to 2004, many countries have seen both a decrease in the rates of fatal burns and in burns generally.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] An estimated 500,000 burn injuries receive medical treatment yearly in the United States.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] They resulted in about 3,300 deaths in 2008.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Most burns (70%) and deaths from burns occur in males.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The highest incidence of fire burns occurs in those 18–35 years old, while the highest incidence of scalds occurs in children less than five years old and adults over 65.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Electrical burns result in about 1,000 deaths per year.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Lightning results in the death of about 60 people a year.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In Europe, intentional burns occur most commonly in middle aged men.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In India, about 700,000 to 800,000 people per year sustain significant burns, though very few are looked after in specialist burn units.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The highest rates occur in women 16–35 years of age.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Part of this high rate is related to unsafe kitchens and loose-fitting clothing typical to India.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] It is estimated that one-third of all burns in India are due to clothing catching fire from open flames.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Intentional burns are also a common cause and occur at high rates in young women, secondary to domestic violence and self-harm.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Cave paintings from more than 3,500 years ago document burns and their management.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The earliest Egyptian records on treating burns describes dressings prepared with milk from mothers of baby boys, and the 1500 BCE Edwin Smith Papyrus describes treatments using honey and the salve of resin.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Many other treatments have been used over the ages, including the use of tea leaves by the Chinese documented to 600 BCE, pig fat and vinegar by Hippocrates documented to 400 BCE, and wine and myrrh by Celsus documented to the 1st century CE.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] French barber-surgeon Ambroise Paré was the first to describe different degrees of burns in the 1500s.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Guillaume Dupuytren expanded these degrees into six different severities in 1832.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The first hospital to treat burns opened in 1843 in London, England, and the development of modern burn care began in the late 1800s and early 1900s.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] Dakin and Alexis Carrel developed standards for the cleaning and disinfecting of burns and wounds using sodium hypochlorite solutions, which significantly reduced mortality.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the 1940s, the importance of early excision and skin grafting was acknowledged, and around the same time, fluid resuscitation and formulas to guide it were developed.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] In the 1970s, researchers demonstrated the significance of the hypermetabolic state that follows large burns.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The "Evans formula", described in 1952, was the first burn resuscitation formula based on body weight and surface area (BSA) damaged.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/burn] The first 24 hours of treatment entails 1ml/kg/% BSA of crystalloids plus 1 ml/kg/% BSA colloids plus 2000ml glucose in water, and in the next 24 hours, crystalloids at 0.5 ml/kg/% BSA, colloids at 0.5 ml/kg/% BSA, and the same amount of glucose in water.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The **Confederate States Navy** (**CSN**) was the naval branch of the Confederate States Armed Forces, established by an act of the Confederate States Congress on February 21, 1861.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] It was responsible for Confederate naval operations during the American Civil War against the United States' Union Navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] It was ineffective in these tasks, as the coastal blockade by the United States Navy reduced trade by the South to 5 percent of its pre-war levels.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Additionally, the control of inland rivers and coastal navigation by the US Navy forced the south to overload its limited railroads to the point of failure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in Liverpool, England, marked the end of the Civil War and the Confederate Navy's existence.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The Confederate Navy could never achieve numerical equality with the Union Navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] It instead sought to take advantage of technological innovation, such as ironclads, submarines, torpedo boats, and naval mines (then known as torpedoes).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] In February 1861, the Confederate States Navy had 30 vessels, only 14 of which were seaworthy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Navy eventually grew to 101 ships to meet the rise in naval conflicts and threats to the coast and rivers of the Confederacy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] On April 20, 1861, the U.S. was forced to quickly abandon the important Gosport Navy Yard at Portsmouth, Virginia.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] In their haste, they failed to effectively burn the facility with its large depots of arms, other supplies, and several small vessels.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] As a result, the Confederacy captured a large supply of much-needed war materials, including heavy cannon, gunpowder, shot, and shell.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Of most importance to the Confederacy was the shipyard's dry docks, barely damaged by the departing Union forces.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The Confederacy's only substantial navy yard at that time was in Pensacola, Florida, so the Gosport Yard was sorely needed to build new warships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The most significant warship left at the Yard was the screw frigate USS *Merrimack*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Navy had torched *Merrimack'*s superstructure and upper deck, then scuttled the vessel; it would have been immediately useful as a warship to their enemy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Little of the ship's structure remained other than the hull, which was holed by the scuttling charge but otherwise intact.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Confederate Navy Secretary Stephen Mallory had the idea to raise *Merrimack* and rebuild it.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] When the hull was raised, it had not been submerged long enough to have been rendered unusable; the steam engines and essential machinery were salvageable.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The decks were rebuilt using thick oak and pine planking, and the upper deck was overlaid with two courses of heavy iron plate.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The newly rebuilt superstructure was unusual: above the waterline, the sides sloped inward and were covered with two layers of heavy iron-plate armor, the inside course laid horizontally, the outside course laid vertically.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The vessel was a new kind of warship, an all-steam powered "iron-clad".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] In the centuries-old tradition of reusing captured ships, the new warship was christened CSS *Virginia*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] She later fought the Union's new ironclad USS *Monitor*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] On the second day of the Battle of Hampton Roads, the two ships met and each scored numerous hits on the other.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] On the first day of that battle *Virginia*, and the James River Squadron, aggressively attacked and nearly broke the Union Navy's sea blockade of wooden warships, proving the effectiveness of the ironclad concept.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The two ironclads had steamed forward, tried to outflank or ram the other, circled, backed away, and came forward firing again and again, but neither was able to sink or demand surrender of its opponent.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] After four hours, both ships were taking on water through split seams and breaches from enemy shot.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The engines of both ships were becoming dangerously overtaxed, and their crews were near exhaustion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The two ships turned and steamed away, never to meet again.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] This part in the Battle of Hampton Roads between *Monitor* and *Virginia* greatly overshadowed the bloody events each side's ground troops were fighting, largely because it was the first battle in history between two iron-armored steam-powered warships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The last Confederate surrender took place in Liverpool, United Kingdom on November 6, 1865, aboard the commerce raider CSS *Shenandoah* when her flag (battle ensign) was lowered for the final time.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] This surrender brought about the end of the Confederate navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The *Shenandoah* had circumnavigated the globe, the only Confederate ship to do so.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The act of the Confederate Congress that created the Confederate Navy on February 21, 1861, also appointed Stephen Mallory as Secretary of the Department of the Navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Mallory was experienced as an admiralty lawyer and had served for a time as the chairman of the Naval Affairs Committee of the United States Senate.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The Confederacy had a few scattered naval assets and looked to Liverpool, England, to buy naval cruisers to attack the American merchant fleet.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] In April 1861, Mallory recruited former U.S.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Navy Lieutenant James Dunwoody Bulloch into the Confederate navy and sent him to Liverpool.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Using Charleston-based importer and exporter Fraser Trentholm, who had offices in Liverpool, Commander Bulloch immediately ordered six steam vessels.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] In addition to the ships included in the report of the committee, the C.S.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Navy also had one ironclad floating battery, presented to the Confederacy by the state of Georgia, one ironclad ram donated by the state of Alabama, and numerous commerce raiders making war on Union merchant ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] When Virginia seceded the Virginia Navy was absorbed into the Confederate Navy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Changes to these regulations were made during 1863, when a new naval jack, battle ensign, and commissioning pennant design was introduced aboard all Confederate ships, echoing the Confederacy's change of its national flag from the old "Stars and Bars" to the new "Stainless Banner".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Despite the detailed naval regulations issued, minor variations in the flags were frequently seen, due to different manufacturing techniques employed, suppliers used, and the flag-making traditions of each southern state.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] President Davis was not confident of his executive authority to issue letters of marque and called a special session of Congress on April 29 to formally authorize the hiring of privateers in the name of the Confederate States.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Both acts granted the president power to issue letters of marque and detailed regulations as to the conditions on which letters of marque should be granted to private vessels, the conduct and behavior of the officers and crews of such vessels, and the disposal of such prizes made by privateer crews.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The manner in which Confederate privateers operated was generally similar to those of privateers of the United States or of European nations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The 1856 Declaration of Paris outlawed privateering for such nations as the United Kingdom and France, but the United States had neither signed nor endorsed the declaration.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Therefore, privateering was constitutionally legal in both the United States and the Confederacy, as well as Portugal, Russia, the Ottoman Empire, and Germany.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] However, the United States did not acknowledge the Confederacy as an independent country and denied the legitimacy of any letters of marque issued by its government.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] President Abraham Lincoln declared all medicines to the Confederacy to be contraband and any captured Confederate privateers were to be hanged as pirates.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Ultimately, no one was hanged for privateering because the Confederate government threatened to retaliate against U.S. prisoners of war.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Initially, Confederate privateers operated primarily from New Orleans, but activity was soon concentrated in the Atlantic, as the Union Navy began expanding its operations.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Confederate privateers harassed Union merchant ships and sank several warships, although they were unable to relieve the blockade on Southern ports and its dire effects on the Confederate economy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] In May 1861, Confederate Congress appropriated $2,000,000 to either construct or purchase ironclad vessels in England.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The Confederacy intended to use the European ironclads to break the Union blockade.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Aside from those built in Europe, the Confederacy also manufactured their own vessels.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Despite a lack of materials (especially iron and engines) and shipbuilding facilities, the Confederacy was able to construct at least twenty ironclads that were commissioned and put into operation during the war.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] One of the more well-known ships was the CSS *Virginia*, formerly the sloop-of-war USS *Merrimack* (1855).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] In 1862, after being converted to an ironclad ram, she fought USS *Monitor* in the Battle of Hampton Roads, an event that came to symbolize the end of the dominance of large wooden sailing warships and the beginning of the age of steam and the ironclad warship.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The Confederates also constructed submarines, among the few that existed after the early *Turtle* of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Of those the *Pioneer* and the Bayou St.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] However, *Hunley*, built in Mobile as a privateer by Horace Hunley, later came under the control of the Confederate Army at Charleston, SC, but was manned partly by a C.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Navy crew; she became the first submarine to sink a ship in a wartime engagement.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The *Hunley* later sank the sloop-of-war USS *Housatonic*, resulting from the large blastwave that traveled from its exploding spar torpedo's 500-pound black powder charge, during the sinking of USS Housatonic.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The sinking of the Housatonic became the first successful submarine attack in history.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Confederate Navy commerce raiders were also used with great success to disrupt U.S. merchant shipping.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The most famous of them was the screw sloop-of-war CSS *Alabama*, a warship secretly built for the Confederacy in Birkenhead, near Liverpool, United Kingdom.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] She was launched as *Enrica* but was commissioned as CSS *Alabama* just off the Azores by her captain, Raphael Semmes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] She began her world-famous raiding career under his command, accounting for 65 U.S. ships, a record that still remains unbeaten by any ship in naval warfare.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] CSS *Alabama*'s crew was mostly from Liverpool, and the cruiser never once dropped anchor in a Confederate port, though she sank a blockading Union gunboat off the coast of Texas.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] She was sunk in June 1864 by USS *Kearsarge* at the Battle of Cherbourg outside the port of Cherbourg, France.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] A similar raider, CSS *Shenandoah*, fired the last shot of the American Civil War in late June 1865; she did not strike her colors and surrender until early November 1865, in Liverpool, England five months after the conflict had ended.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Between the beginning of the war and the end of 1861, 373 commissioned officers, warrant officers, and midshipmen had resigned or been dismissed from the United States Navy and had gone on to serve the Confederacy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The Provisional Congress meeting in Montgomery accepted these men into the Confederate Navy at their old rank.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] In order to accommodate them they initially provided for an officer corps to consist of four captains, four commanders, 30 lieutenants, and various other non-line officers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] The Department of the Navy was responsible for the administration of the affairs of the Confederate Navy and Confederate Marine Corps.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] It included various offices, bureaus, and naval agents in Europe.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] By 1862 regulations specified the uniforms and rank insignia for officers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Petty officers wore a variety of uniforms, or even regular clothing.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Officers of the Confederate States Navy used, just like the army, a combination of several rank insignias to indicate their rank.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] While both hat insignia and sleeve insignia were used here the primary indicator were shoulder straps.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Only line officers wore those straps shown below as officers of various staff departments (Medical, Pay, Engineering and Naval Construction) had separate ranks and different straps.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Likewise the anchor symbol on the hats was substituted accordingly and they did not wear loops on the sleeve insignias.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Paymasters, surgeons and chief engineers of more than twelve year's standing ranked with commanders.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Paymasters, surgeons and chief engineers of less than twelve year's standing ranked with lieutenants.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Assistant paymasters ranked with masters during the first five years of service, then with lieutenants.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Passed assistant surgeons and professors ranked with masters.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Assistant surgeons, first assistant engineers and secretaries to commanders of squadrons ranked with passed midshipmen.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] Second and third assistant engineers and clerks to commanding officers and paymasters ranked as midshipmen.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] According to length of commissioned service.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/confederate-states-navy] According to length of warrant sea service.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] A **diesel engine** is an internal combustion engine in which ignition of diesel fuel is caused by the elevated temperature of the air in the cylinder due to mechanical compression; thus, the diesel engine is also called a **compression-ignition engine** (or **CI engine**).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This contrasts with engines using spark plug-ignition of the air-fuel mixture, such as a petrol engine (gasoline engine) or a gas engine (using a gaseous fuel like natural gas or liquefied petroleum gas).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The diesel engine is named after its inventor, German engineer Rudolf Diesel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel engines work by compressing only air, or air combined with residual combustion gases from the exhaust (known as exhaust gas recirculation, "EGR").
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Air is inducted into the chamber during the intake stroke, and compressed during the compression stroke.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This increases air temperature inside the cylinder so that atomised diesel fuel injected into the combustion chamber ignites.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The torque a diesel engine produces is controlled by manipulating the air-fuel ratio (λ); instead of throttling the intake air, the diesel engine relies on altering the amount of fuel that is injected, and thus the air-fuel ratio is usually high.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The diesel engine has the highest thermal efficiency *(see engine efficiency)* of any practical internal or external combustion engine due to its very high expansion ratio and inherent lean burn, which enables heat dissipation by excess air.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] A small efficiency loss is also avoided compared with non-direct-injection gasoline engines, as unburned fuel is not present during valve overlap, and therefore no fuel goes directly from the intake/injection to the exhaust.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Low-speed diesel engines (as used in ships and other applications where overall engine weight is relatively unimportant) can reach effective efficiencies of up to 55%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The combined cycle gas turbine (Brayton and Rankine cycle) is a combustion engine that is more efficient than a diesel engine, but due to its mass and dimensions, is unsuitable for many vehicles, including aircraft and some watercraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The world's largest diesel engines put in service are 14-cylinder, two-stroke marine diesel engines; they produce a peak power of almost 100 MW each.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel engines may be designed with either two-stroke or four-stroke combustion cycles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] They were originally used as a more efficient replacement for stationary steam engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Since the 1910s, they have been used in submarines and ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Use in locomotives, buses, trucks, heavy equipment, agricultural equipment and electricity generation plants followed later.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In the 1930s, they slowly began to be used in some automobiles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Since the 1970s energy crisis, demand for higher fuel efficiency has resulted in most major automakers, at some point, offering diesel-powered models, even in very small cars.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] According to Konrad Reif (2012), the EU average for diesel cars at the time accounted for half of newly registered cars.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] However, air pollution and overall emissions are more difficult to control in diesel engines compared to gasoline engines, so the use of diesel engines in the US is now largely relegated to larger on-road and off-road vehicles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Though aviation has traditionally avoided using diesel engines, aircraft diesel engines have become increasingly available in the 21st century.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In 1878, Rudolf Diesel, who was a student at the "Polytechnikum" in Munich, attended the lectures of Carl von Linde.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Linde explained that steam engines are capable of converting just 6–10% of the heat energy into work, but that the Carnot cycle allows conversion of much more of the heat energy into work by means of isothermal change in condition.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] According to Diesel, this ignited the idea of creating a highly efficient engine that could work on the Carnot cycle.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel was also introduced to a fire piston, a traditional fire starter using rapid adiabatic compression principles which Linde had acquired from Southeast Asia.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] After several years of working on his ideas, Diesel published them in 1893 in the essay *Theory and Construction of a Rational Heat Motor*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel was heavily criticised for his essay, but only a few found the mistake that he made; his *rational heat motor* was supposed to utilise a constant temperature cycle (with isothermal compression) that would require a much higher level of compression than that needed for compression ignition.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel's idea was to compress the air so tightly that the temperature of the air would exceed that of combustion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] However, such an engine could never perform any usable work.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] By June 1893, Diesel had realised his original cycle would not work, and he adopted the constant pressure cycle.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel describes the cycle in his 1895 patent application.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Notice that there is no longer a mention of compression temperatures exceeding the temperature of combustion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Now it is simply stated that the compression must be sufficient to trigger ignition.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In 1892, Diesel received patents in Germany, Switzerland, the United Kingdom, and the United States for "Method of and Apparatus for Converting Heat into Work".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In 1894 and 1895, he filed patents and addenda in various countries for his engine; the first patents were issued in Spain (No.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel was attacked and criticised over several years.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Critics claimed that Diesel never invented a new motor and that the invention of the diesel engine is fraud.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Otto Köhler and Emil Capitaine were two of the most prominent critics of Diesel's time.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Köhler had published an essay in 1887, in which he describes an engine similar to the engine Diesel describes in his 1893 essay.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Köhler figured that such an engine could not perform any work.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Emil Capitaine had built a petroleum engine with glow-tube ignition in the early 1890s; he claimed against his own better judgement that his glow-tube ignition engine worked the same way Diesel's engine did.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] His claims were unfounded and he lost a patent lawsuit against Diesel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Other engines, such as the Akroyd engine and the Brayton engine, also use an operating cycle that is different from the diesel engine cycle.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Friedrich Sass says that the diesel engine is Diesel's "very own work" and that any "Diesel myth" is "falsification of history".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel sought out firms and factories that would build his engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] With the help of Moritz Schröter and Max Gutermuth, he succeeded in convincing both Krupp in Essen and the Maschinenfabrik Augsburg.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Contracts were signed in April 1893, and in early summer 1893, Diesel's first prototype engine was built in Augsburg.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] On 10 August 1893, the first ignition took place, the fuel used was petrol.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In winter 1893/1894, Diesel redesigned the existing engine, and by 18 January 1894, his mechanics had converted it into the second prototype.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] During January that year, an air-blast injection system was added to the engine's cylinder head and tested.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Friedrich Sass argues that, it can be presumed that Diesel copied the concept of air-blast injection from George B.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Brayton, albeit that Diesel substantially improved the system.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] On 17 February 1894, the redesigned engine ran for 88 revolutions – one minute; with this news, Maschinenfabrik Augsburg's stock rose by 30%, indicative of the tremendous anticipated demands for a more efficient engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] On 26 June 1895, the engine achieved an effective efficiency of 16.6% and had a fuel consumption of 519 g·kW−1·h−1.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] However, despite proving the concept, the engine caused problems, and Diesel could not achieve any substantial progress.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Therefore, Krupp considered rescinding the contract they had made with Diesel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel was forced to improve the design of his engine and rushed to construct a third prototype engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Between 8 November and 20 December 1895, the second prototype had successfully covered over 111 hours on the test bench.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In the January 1896 report, this was considered a success.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In February 1896, Diesel considered supercharging the third prototype.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Imanuel Lauster, who was ordered to draw the third prototype "Motor 250/400", had finished the drawings by 30 April 1896.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] During summer that year the engine was built, it was completed on 6 October 1896.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] First public tests began on 1 February 1897.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Moritz Schröter's test on 17 February 1897 was the main test of Diesel's engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The engine was rated 13.1 kW with a specific fuel consumption of 324 g·kW−1·h−1, resulting in an effective efficiency of 26.2%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] By 1898, Diesel had become a millionaire.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The diesel internal combustion engine differs from the gasoline powered Otto cycle by using highly compressed hot air to ignite the fuel rather than using a spark plug (*compression ignition* rather than *spark ignition*).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In the diesel engine, only air is initially introduced into the combustion chamber.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The air is then compressed with a compression ratio typically between 15:1 and 23:1.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This high compression causes the temperature of the air to rise.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] At about the top of the compression stroke, fuel is injected directly into the compressed air in the combustion chamber.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This may be into a (typically toroidal) void in the top of the piston or a *pre-chamber* depending upon the design of the engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The fuel injector ensures that the fuel is broken down into small droplets, and that the fuel is distributed evenly.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The heat of the compressed air vaporises fuel from the surface of the droplets.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The vapour is then ignited by the heat from the compressed air in the combustion chamber, the droplets continue to vaporise from their surfaces and burn, getting smaller, until all the fuel in the droplets has been burnt.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Combustion occurs at a substantially constant pressure during the initial part of the power stroke.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The start of vaporisation causes a delay before ignition and the characteristic diesel knocking sound as the vapour reaches ignition temperature and causes an abrupt increase in pressure above the piston (not shown on the P-V indicator diagram).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] When combustion is complete the combustion gases expand as the piston descends further; the high pressure in the cylinder drives the piston downward, supplying power to the crankshaft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] As well as the high level of compression allowing combustion to take place without a separate ignition system, a high compression ratio greatly increases the engine's efficiency.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Increasing the compression ratio in a spark-ignition engine where fuel and air are mixed before entry to the cylinder is limited by the need to prevent pre-ignition, which would cause engine damage.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Since only air is compressed in a diesel engine, and fuel is not introduced into the cylinder until shortly before top dead centre (TDC), premature detonation is not a problem and compression ratios are much higher.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The pressure–volume diagram (pV) diagram is a simplified and idealised representation of the events involved in a diesel engine cycle, arranged to illustrate the similarity with a Carnot cycle.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Starting at 1, the piston is at bottom dead centre and both valves are closed at the start of the compression stroke; the cylinder contains air at atmospheric pressure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Between 1 and 2 the air is compressed adiabatically – that is without heat transfer to or from the environment – by the rising piston.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] (This is only approximately true since there will be some heat exchange with the cylinder walls.) During this compression, the volume is reduced, the pressure and temperature both rise.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] At or slightly before 2 (TDC) fuel is injected and burns in the compressed hot air.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Chemical energy is released and this constitutes an injection of thermal energy (heat) into the compressed gas.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Combustion and heating occur between 2 and 3.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In this interval the pressure remains constant since the piston descends, and the volume increases; the temperature rises as a consequence of the energy of combustion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] At 3 fuel injection and combustion are complete, and the cylinder contains gas at a higher temperature than at 2.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Between 3 and 4 this hot gas expands, again approximately adiabatically.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Work is done on the system to which the engine is connected.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] During this expansion phase the volume of the gas rises, and its temperature and pressure both fall.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] At 4 the exhaust valve opens, and the pressure falls abruptly to atmospheric (approximately).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This is unresisted expansion and no useful work is done by it.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] After the opening of the exhaust valve, the exhaust stroke follows, but this (and the following induction stroke) are not shown on the diagram.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] If shown, they would be represented by a low-pressure loop at the bottom of the diagram.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] At 1 it is assumed that the exhaust and induction strokes have been completed, and the cylinder is again filled with air.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The piston-cylinder system absorbs energy between 1 and 2 – this is the work needed to compress the air in the cylinder, and is provided by mechanical kinetic energy stored in the flywheel of the engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Work output is done by the piston-cylinder combination between 2 and 4.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The difference between these two increments of work is the indicated work output per cycle, and is represented by the area enclosed by the pV loop.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The adiabatic expansion is in a higher pressure range than that of the compression because the gas in the cylinder is hotter during expansion than during compression.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] It is for this reason that the loop has a finite area, and the net output of work during a cycle is positive.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The fuel efficiency of diesel engines is better than most other types of combustion engines, due to their high compression ratio, high air–fuel equivalence ratio (λ), and the lack of intake air restrictions (i.e. throttle valves).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Theoretically, the highest possible efficiency for a diesel engine is 75%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] However, in practice the efficiency is much lower, with efficiencies of up to 43% for passenger car engines, up to 45% for large truck and bus engines, and up to 55% for large two-stroke marine engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The average efficiency over a motor vehicle driving cycle is lower than the diesel engine's peak efficiency (for example, a 37% average efficiency for an engine with a peak efficiency of 44%).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] That is because the fuel efficiency of a diesel engine drops at lower loads, however, it does not drop quite as fast as the Otto (spark ignition) engine's.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Diesel engines are combustion engines and, therefore, emit combustion products in their exhaust gas.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Due to incomplete combustion, diesel engine exhaust gases include carbon monoxide, hydrocarbons, particulate matter, and nitrogen oxides pollutants.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] About 90 per cent of the pollutants can be removed from the exhaust gas using exhaust gas treatment technology.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Road vehicle diesel engines have no sulfur dioxide emissions, because motor vehicle diesel fuel has been sulfur-free since 2003.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Helmut Tschöke argues that particulate matter emitted from motor vehicles has negative impacts on human health.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The particulate matter in diesel exhaust emissions is sometimes classified as a carcinogen or "probable carcinogen" and is known to increase the risk of heart and respiratory diseases.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In principle, a diesel engine does not require any sort of electrical system.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] However, most modern diesel engines are equipped with an electrical fuel pump, and an electronic engine control unit.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] However, there is no high-voltage electrical ignition system present in a diesel engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This eliminates a source of radio frequency emissions (which can interfere with navigation and communication equipment), which is why only diesel-powered vehicles are allowed in some parts of the American National Radio Quiet Zone.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] To control the torque output at any given time (i.e. when the driver of a car adjusts the accelerator pedal), a governor adjusts the amount of fuel injected into the engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Mechanical governors have been used in the past, however electronic governors are more common on modern engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Mechanical governors are usually driven by the engine's accessory belt or a gear-drive system and use a combination of springs and weights to control fuel delivery relative to both load and speed.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Electronically governed engines use an electronic control unit (ECU) or electronic control module (ECM) to control the fuel delivery.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The ECM/ECU uses various sensors (such as engine speed signal, intake manifold pressure and fuel temperature) to determine the amount of fuel injected into the engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Due to the amount of air being constant (for a given RPM) while the amount of fuel varies, very high ("lean") air-fuel ratios are used in situations where minimal torque output is required.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This differs from a petrol engine, where a throttle is used to also reduce the amount of intake air as part of regulating the engine's torque output.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Controlling the timing of the start of injection of fuel into the cylinder is similar to controlling the ignition timing in a petrol engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] It is therefore a key factor in controlling the power output, fuel consumption and exhaust emissions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] There are several different ways of categorising diesel engines, as outlined in the following sections.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] High-speed engines are used to power trucks (lorries), buses, tractors, cars, yachts, compressors, pumps and small electrical generators.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] As of 2018, most high-speed engines have direct injection.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Many modern engines, particularly in on-highway applications, have common rail direct injection.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] On bigger ships, high-speed diesel engines are often used for powering electric generators.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The highest power output of high-speed diesel engines is approximately 5 MW.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Medium-speed engines are used in large electrical generators, railway diesel locomotives, ship propulsion and mechanical drive applications such as large compressors or pumps.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Medium speed diesel engines operate on either diesel fuel or heavy fuel oil by direct injection in the same manner as low-speed engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Usually, they are four-stroke engines with trunk pistons; a notable exception being the EMD 567, 645, and 710 engines, which are all two-stroke.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The power output of medium-speed diesel engines can be as high as 21,870 kW, with the effective efficiency being around 47-48% (1982).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Most larger medium-speed engines are started with compressed air direct on pistons, using an air distributor, as opposed to a pneumatic starting motor acting on the flywheel, which tends to be used for smaller engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Medium-speed engines intended for marine applications are usually used to power (ro-ro) ferries, passenger ships or small freight ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Using medium-speed engines reduces the cost of smaller ships and increases their transport capacity.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] In addition to that, a single ship can use two smaller engines instead of one big engine, which increases the ship's safety.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Low-speed diesel engines are usually very large in size and mostly used to power ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] There are two different types of low-speed engines that are commonly used: Two-stroke engines with a crosshead, and four-stroke engines with a regular trunk-piston.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Two-stroke engines have a limited rotational frequency and their charge exchange is more difficult, which means that they are usually bigger than four-stroke engines and used to directly power a ship's propeller.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Four-stroke engines on ships are usually used to power an electric generator.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Both types are usually very undersquare, meaning the bore is smaller than the stroke.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Low-speed diesel engines (as used in ships and other applications where overall engine weight is relatively unimportant) often have an effective efficiency of up to 55%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Like medium-speed engines, low-speed engines are started with compressed air, and they use heavy oil as their primary fuel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Four-stroke engines use the combustion cycle described earlier.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Most smaller diesels, for vehicular use, for instance, typically use the four-stroke cycle.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This is due to several factors, such as the two-stroke design's narrow powerband which is not particularly suitable for automotive use and the necessity for complicated and expensive built-in lubrication systems and scavenging measures.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The cost effectiveness (and proportion of added weight) of these technologies has less of an impact on larger, more expensive engines, while engines intended for shipping or stationary use can be run at a single speed for long periods.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Two-stroke engines use a combustion cycle which is completed in two strokes instead of four strokes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Filling the cylinder with air and compressing it takes place in one stroke, and the power and exhaust strokes are combined.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The compression in a two-stroke diesel engine is similar to the compression that takes place in a four-stroke diesel engine: As the piston passes through bottom centre and starts upward, compression commences, culminating in fuel injection and ignition.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Instead of a full set of valves, two-stroke diesel engines have simple intake ports, and exhaust ports (or exhaust valves).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] When the piston approaches bottom dead centre, both the intake and the exhaust ports are "open", which means that there is atmospheric pressure inside the cylinder.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Therefore, some sort of pump is required to blow the air into the cylinder and the combustion gasses into the exhaust.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The pressure required is approximately 10-30 kPa.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Due to the lack of discrete exhaust and intake strokes, all two-stroke diesel engines use a scavenge blower or some form of compressor to charge the cylinders with air and assist in scavenging.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Roots-type superchargers were used for ship engines until the mid-1950s, however since 1955 they have been widely replaced by turbochargers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Usually, a two-stroke ship diesel engine has a single-stage turbocharger with a turbine that has an axial inflow and a radial outflow.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Crossflow scavenging is incomplete and limits the stroke, yet some manufacturers used it.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Reverse flow scavenging is a very simple way of scavenging, and it was popular amongst manufacturers until the early 1980s.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Uniflow scavenging is more complicated to make but allows the highest fuel efficiency; since the early 1980s, manufacturers such as MAN and Sulzer have switched to this system.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] It is standard for modern marine two-stroke diesel engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] So-called dual-fuel diesel engines or gas diesel engines burn two different types of fuel *simultaneously*, for instance, a gaseous fuel and diesel engine fuel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The diesel engine fuel auto-ignites due to compression ignition, and then ignites the gaseous fuel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Such engines do not require any type of spark ignition and operate similar to regular diesel engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The fuel is injected at high pressure into either the combustion chamber, "swirl chamber" or "pre-chamber," unlike petrol engines where the fuel is often added in the inlet manifold or carburetor.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Engines where the fuel is injected into the main combustion chamber are called direct injection (DI) engines, while those which use a swirl chamber or pre-chamber are called indirect injection (IDI) engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Most direct injection diesel engines have a combustion cup in the top of the piston where the fuel is sprayed.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Many different methods of injection can be used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Usually, an engine with helix-controlled mechanic direct injection has either an inline or a distributor injection pump.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] For each engine cylinder, the corresponding plunger in the fuel pump measures out the correct amount of fuel and determines the timing of each injection.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] These engines use injectors that are very precise spring-loaded valves that open and close at a specific fuel pressure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Separate high-pressure fuel lines connect the fuel pump with each cylinder.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Fuel volume for each single combustion is controlled by a slanted groove in the plunger which rotates only a few degrees releasing the pressure and is controlled by a mechanical governor, consisting of weights rotating at engine speed constrained by springs and a lever.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The injectors are held open by the fuel pressure.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] On high-speed engines the plunger pumps are together in one unit.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The length of fuel lines from the pump to each injector is normally the same for each cylinder in order to obtain the same pressure delay.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Direct injected diesel engines usually use orifice-type fuel injectors.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Electronic control of the fuel injection transformed the direct injection engine by allowing much greater control over the combustion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Common rail (CR) direct injection systems do not have the fuel metering, pressure-raising and delivery functions in a single unit, as in the case of a Bosch distributor-type pump, for example.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The requirements of each cylinder injector are supplied from this common high pressure reservoir of fuel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] An Electronic Diesel Control (EDC) controls both rail pressure and injections depending on engine operating conditions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The injectors of older CR systems have solenoid-driven plungers for lifting the injection needle, whilst newer CR injectors use plungers driven by piezoelectric actuators that have less moving mass and therefore allow even more injections in a very short period of time.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Early common rail system were controlled by mechanical means.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The injection pressure of modern CR systems ranges from 140 MPa to 270 MPa.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] An indirect diesel injection system (IDI) engine delivers fuel into a small chamber called a swirl chamber, precombustion chamber, pre chamber or ante-chamber, which is connected to the cylinder by a narrow air passage.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Generally the goal of the pre chamber is to create increased turbulence for better air / fuel mixing.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This system also allows for a smoother, quieter running engine, and because fuel mixing is assisted by turbulence, injector pressures can be lower.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Most IDI systems use a single orifice injector.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The pre-chamber has the disadvantage of lowering efficiency due to increased heat loss to the engine's cooling system, restricting the combustion burn, thus reducing the efficiency by 5–10%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] IDI engines are also more difficult to start and usually require the use of glow plugs.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] IDI engines may be cheaper to build but generally require a higher compression ratio than the DI counterpart.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] IDI also makes it easier to produce smooth, quieter running engines with a simple mechanical injection system since exact injection timing is not as critical.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Most modern automotive engines are DI which have the benefits of greater efficiency and easier starting; however, IDI engines can still be found in the many ATV and small diesel applications.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Indirect injected diesel engines use pintle-type fuel injectors.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Early diesel engines injected fuel with the assistance of compressed air, which atomised the fuel and forced it into the engine through a nozzle (a similar principle to an aerosol spray).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] The nozzle opening was closed by a pin valve actuated by the camshaft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Although the engine was also required to drive an air compressor used for air-blast injection, the efficiency was nonetheless better than other combustion engines of the time.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] However the system was heavy and it was slow to react to changing torque demands, making it unsuitable for road vehicles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] A *unit injector* system, also known as "Pumpe-Düse" (*pump-nozzle* in German) combines the injector and fuel pump into a single component, which is positioned above each cylinder.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] This eliminates the high-pressure fuel lines and achieves a more consistent injection.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Under full load, the injection pressure can reach up to 220 MPa.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Unit injectors are operated by a cam and the quantity of fuel injected is controlled either mechanically (by a rack or lever) or electronically.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p01] Due to increased performance requirements, unit injectors have been largely replaced by common rail injection systems.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The average diesel engine has a poorer power-to-mass ratio than an equivalent petrol engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The lower engine speeds (RPM) of typical diesel engines results in a lower power output.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Also, the mass of a diesel engine is typically higher, since the higher operating pressure inside the combustion chamber increases the internal forces, which requires stronger (and therefore heavier) parts to withstand these forces.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The distinctive noise of a diesel engine, particularly at idling speeds, is sometimes called "diesel clatter".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] This noise is largely caused by the sudden ignition of the diesel fuel when injected into the combustion chamber, which causes a pressure wave that sounds like knocking.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Engine designers can reduce diesel clatter through: indirect injection; pilot or pre-injection; injection timing; injection rate; compression ratio; turbo boost; and exhaust gas recirculation (EGR).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Common rail diesel injection systems permit multiple injection events as an aid to noise reduction.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Through measures such as these, diesel clatter noise is greatly reduced in modern engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel fuels with a higher cetane rating are more likely to ignite and hence reduce diesel clatter.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In warmer climates, diesel engines do not require any starting aid (aside from the starter motor).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] However, many diesel engines include some form of preheating for the combustion chamber, to assist starting in cold conditions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Engines with a displacement of less than 1 litre per cylinder usually have glowplugs, whilst larger heavy-duty engines have flame-start systems.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The minimum starting temperature that allows starting without pre-heating is 40 °C (104 °F) for precombustion chamber engines, 20 °C (68 °F) for swirl chamber engines, and 0 °C (32 °F) for direct injected engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In the past, a wider variety of cold-start methods were used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Some engines, such as Detroit Diesel engines used a system to introduce small amounts of ether into the inlet manifold to start combustion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Instead of glowplugs, some diesel engines are equipped with starting aid systems that change valve timing.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The simplest way this can be done is with a decompression lever.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Activating the decompression lever locks the outlet valves in a slight down position, resulting in the engine not having any compression and thus allowing for turning the crankshaft over with significantly less resistance.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] When the crankshaft reaches a higher speed, flipping the decompression lever back into its normal position will abruptly re-activate the outlet valves, resulting in compression − the flywheel's mass moment of inertia then starts the engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Other diesel engines, such as the precombustion chamber engine XII Jv 170/240 made by Ganz & Co., have a valve timing changing system that is operated by adjusting the inlet valve camshaft, moving it into a slight "late" position.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] This will make the inlet valves open with a delay, forcing the inlet air to heat up when entering the combustion chamber.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Forced induction, especially turbocharging is commonly used on diesel engines because it greatly increases efficiency and torque output.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines are well suited for forced induction setups due to their operating principle which is characterised by wide ignition limits and the absence of fuel during the compression stroke.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Therefore, knocking, pre-ignition or detonation cannot occur, and a lean mixture caused by excess supercharging air inside the combustion chamber does not negatively affect combustion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines can combust a huge variety of fuels, including several fuel oils that have advantages over fuels such as petrol.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In diesel engines, a mechanical injector system atomizes the fuel directly into the combustion chamber (as opposed to a Venturi jet in a carburetor, or a fuel injector in a manifold injection system atomizing fuel into the intake manifold or intake runners as in a petrol engine).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Because only air is inducted into the cylinder in a diesel engine, the compression ratio can be much higher as there is no risk of pre-ignition provided the injection process is accurately timed.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] This means that cylinder temperatures are much higher in a diesel engine than a petrol engine, allowing less volatile fuels to be used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Therefore, diesel engines can operate on a huge variety of different fuels.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In general, fuel for diesel engines should have a proper viscosity, so that the injection pump can pump the fuel to the injection nozzles without causing damage to itself or corrosion of the fuel line.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] At injection, the fuel should form a good fuel spray, and it should not have a coking effect upon the injection nozzles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] To ensure proper engine starting and smooth operation, the fuel should be willing to ignite and hence not cause a high ignition delay, (this means that the fuel should have a high cetane number).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel fuel should also have a high lower heating value.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Inline mechanical injector pumps generally tolerate poor-quality or bio-fuels better than distributor-type pumps.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Also, indirect injection engines generally run more satisfactorily on fuels with a high ignition delay (for instance, petrol) than direct injection engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Direct-injected engines with an MAN centre sphere combustion chamber rely on fuel condensing on the combustion chamber walls.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The fuel starts vaporising only after ignition sets in, and it burns relatively smoothly.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Therefore, such engines also tolerate fuels with poor ignition delay characteristics, and, in general, they can operate on petrol rated 86 RON.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In his 1893 work *Theory and Construction of a Rational Heat Motor*, Rudolf Diesel considers using coal dust as fuel for the diesel engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] However, Diesel just *considered* using coal dust (as well as liquid fuels and gas); his actual engine was designed to operate on petroleum, which was soon replaced with regular petrol and kerosene for further testing purposes, as petroleum proved to be too viscous.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In addition to kerosene and petrol, Diesel's engine could also operate on ligroin.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Before diesel engine fuel was standardised, fuels such as petrol, kerosene, gas oil, vegetable oil and mineral oil, as well as mixtures of these fuels, were used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The first diesel fuel standards were the DIN 51601, VTL 9140-001, and NATO F 54, which appeared after World War II.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The modern European EN 590 diesel fuel standard was established in May 1993; the modern version of the NATO F 54 standard is mostly identical with it.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The DIN 51628 biodiesel standard was rendered obsolete by the 2009 version of the EN 590; FAME biodiesel conforms to the EN 14214 standard.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Watercraft diesel engines usually operate on diesel engine fuel that conforms to the ISO 8217 standard (Bunker C).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Also, some diesel engines can operate on gasses (such as LNG).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] DIN 51601 diesel fuel was prone to *waxing* or *gelling* in cold weather; both are terms for the solidification of diesel oil into a partially crystalline state.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The crystals build up in the fuel system (especially in fuel filters), eventually starving the engine of fuel and causing it to stop running.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Low-output electric heaters in fuel tanks and around fuel lines were used to solve this problem.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Also, most engines have a *spill return* system, by which any excess fuel from the injector pump and injectors is returned to the fuel tank.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Once the engine has warmed, returning warm fuel prevents waxing in the tank.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Before direct injection diesel engines, some manufacturers, such as BMW, recommended mixing up to 30% petrol in with the diesel by fuelling diesel cars with petrol to prevent the fuel from gelling when the temperatures dropped below −15 °C.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel fuel is less flammable than petrol, because its flash point is 55 °C, leading to a lower risk of fire caused by fuel in a vehicle equipped with a diesel engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel fuel can create an explosive air/vapour mix under the right conditions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] However, compared with petrol, it is less prone due to its lower vapour pressure, which is an indication of evaporation rate.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The Material Safety Data Sheet for ultra-low sulfur diesel fuel indicates a vapour explosion hazard for diesel fuel indoors, outdoors, or in sewers.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel exhaust has been classified as an IARC Group 1 carcinogen.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] It causes lung cancer and is associated with an increased risk for bladder cancer.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The characteristics of diesel have different advantages for different applications.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines have long been popular in bigger cars and have been used in smaller cars such as superminis in Europe since the 1980s.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] They were popular in larger cars earlier, as the weight and cost penalties were less noticeable.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Smooth operation as well as high low-end torque are deemed important for passenger cars and small commercial vehicles.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The introduction of electronically controlled fuel injection significantly improved the smooth torque generation, and starting in the early 1990s, car manufacturers began offering their high-end luxury vehicles with diesel engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Passenger car diesel engines usually have between three and twelve cylinders, and a displacement ranging from 0.8 to 6.0 litres.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Modern powerplants are usually turbocharged and have direct injection.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines do not suffer from intake-air throttling, resulting in very low fuel consumption especially at low partial load (for instance: driving at city speeds).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] One fifth of all passenger cars worldwide have diesel engines, with many of them being in Europe, where approximately 47% of all passenger cars are diesel-powered.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Daimler-Benz in conjunction with Robert Bosch GmbH produced diesel-powered passenger cars starting in 1936.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The popularity of diesel-powered passenger cars in markets such as India, South Korea and Japan is increasing (as of 2018).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In 1893, Rudolf Diesel suggested that the diesel engine could possibly power "wagons" (lorries).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The first lorries with diesel engines were brought to market in 1924.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Modern diesel engines for lorries have to be both extremely reliable and very fuel efficient.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Common-rail direct injection, turbocharging and four valves per cylinder are standard.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Displacements range from 4.5 to 15.5 litres, with power-to-mass ratios of 2.5–3.5 kg·kW−1 for heavy duty and 2.0–3.0 kg·kW−1 for medium duty engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] V6 and V8 engines used to be common, due to the relatively low engine mass the V configuration provides.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Recently, the V configuration has been abandoned in favour of straight engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] These engines are usually straight-6 for heavy and medium duties and straight-4 for medium duty.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Their undersquare design causes lower overall piston speeds which results in increased lifespan of up to 1,200,000 kilometres (750,000 mi).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Compared with 1970s diesel engines, the expected lifespan of modern lorry diesel engines has more than doubled.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines for locomotives are built for continuous operation between refuelings and may need to be designed to use poor quality fuel in some circumstances.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Some locomotives use two-stroke diesel engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines have replaced steam engines on all non-electrified railroads in the world.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The first diesel locomotives appeared in 1913, and diesel multiple units soon after.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Nearly all modern diesel locomotives are more correctly known as diesel–electric locomotives because they use an electric transmission: the diesel engine drives an electric generator which powers electric traction motors.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] While electric locomotives have replaced the diesel locomotive for passenger services in many areas diesel traction is widely used for cargo-hauling freight trains and on tracks where electrification is not economically viable.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In the 1940s, road vehicle diesel engines with power outputs of 150–200 metric horsepower (110–150 kW; 150–200 hp) were considered reasonable for DMUs.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Commonly, regular truck powerplants were used.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The height of these engines had to be less than 1 metre (3 ft 3 in) to allow underfloor installation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Usually, the engine was mated with a pneumatically operated mechanical gearbox, due to the low size, mass, and production costs of this design.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Some DMUs used hydraulic torque converters instead.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel–electric transmission was not suitable for such small engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In the 1930s, the Deutsche Reichsbahn standardised its first DMU engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] It was a 30.3 litres (1,850 cu in), 12-cylinder boxer unit, producing 275 metric horsepower (202 kW; 271 hp).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Several German manufacturers produced engines according to this standard.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The requirements for marine diesel engines vary, depending on the application.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] For military use and medium-size boats, medium-speed four-stroke diesel engines are most suitable.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] These engines usually have up to 24 cylinders and come with power outputs in the one-digit Megawatt region.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Small boats may use lorry diesel engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Large ships use extremely efficient, low-speed two-stroke diesel engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] They can reach efficiencies of up to 55%.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Unlike most regular diesel engines, two-stroke watercraft engines use highly viscous fuel oil.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The first diesel engines for ships were made by A.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] These engines were three-cylinder units of 120 PS (88 kW) and four-cylinder units of 180 PS (132 kW) and used for Russian ships.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In World War I, especially submarine diesel engine development advanced quickly.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] By the end of the War, double acting piston two-stroke engines with up to 12,200 PS (9 MW) had been made for marine use.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines had been used in aircraft before World War II, for instance, in the rigid airship *LZ 129 Hindenburg,* which was powered by four Daimler-Benz DB 602 diesel engines, or in several Junkers aircraft, which had Jumo 205 engines installed.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In 1929, in the United States, the Packard Motor Company developed America's first aircraft diesel engine, the Packard DR-980—an air-cooled, 9-cylinder radial engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Additional advantages cited, at the time, included a lower risk of post-crash fire, and superior performance at high altitudes.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] On March 6, 1930, the engine received an Approved Type Certificate—first ever for an aircraft diesel engine—from the U.S.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] However, noxious exhaust fumes, cold-start and vibration problems, engine structural failures, the death of its developer, and the industrial economic contraction of the Great Depression, combined to kill the program.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] From then, until the late 1970s, there had not been many applications of the diesel engine in aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In 1978, Piper Cherokee co-designer Karl H.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] However, with the 1970s energy crisis and environmental movement, and resulting pressures for greater fuel economy, reduced carbon and lead in the atmosphere, and other issues, there was a resurgence of interest in diesel engines for aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] High-compression piston aircraft engines that run on aviation gasoline ("avgas") generally require the addition of toxic Tetraethyl lead to avgas, to avoid engine pre-ignition and detonation; but diesel engines do not require leaded fuel.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Also, biodiesel can, theoretically, provide a net reduction in atmospheric carbon compared to avgas.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] For these reasons, the general aviation community has begun to fear the possible banning or discontinuance of leaded avgas.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Additionally, avgas is a specialty fuel in very low (and declining) demand, compared to other fuels, and its makers are susceptible to costly aviation-crash lawsuits, reducing refiners' interest in producing it.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Outside the United States, avgas has already become increasingly difficult to find at airports (and generally), than less-expensive, diesel-compatible fuels like Jet-A and other jet fuels.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] By the late 1990s / early 2000s, diesel engines were beginning to appear in light aircraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Most notably, Frank Thielert and his Austrian engine enterprise, began developing diesel engines to replace the 100 horsepower (75 kW) - 350 horsepower (260 kW) gasoline/piston engines in common light aircraft use.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] First successful application of the Theilerts to production aircraft was in the Diamond DA42 Twin Star light twin, which exhibited exceptional fuel efficiency surpassing anything in its class, and its single-engined predecessor, the Diamond DA40 Diamond Star.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In subsequent years, several other companies have developed aircraft diesel engines, or have begun to—most notably Continental Aerospace Technologies which, by 2018, was reporting it had sold over 5,000 such engines worldwide.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The United States' Federal Aviation Administration has reported that "by 2007, various jet-fueled piston aircraft had logged well over 600,000 hours of service".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In recent years (2016), diesel engines have also found use in unmanned aircraft (UAV), due to their reliability, durability, and low fuel consumption.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Non-road diesel engines are commonly used for construction equipment and agricultural machinery.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Fuel efficiency, reliability and ease of maintenance are very important for such engines, whilst high power output and quiet operation are negligible.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Therefore, mechanically controlled fuel injection and air-cooling are still very common.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The common power outputs of non-road diesel engines vary a lot, with the smallest units starting at 3 kW, and the most powerful engines being heavy duty lorry engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Stationary diesel engines are commonly used for electricity generation, but also for powering refrigerator compressors, or other types of compressors or pumps.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Usually, these engines either run continuously with partial load, or intermittently with full load.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Stationary diesel engines powering electric generators that put out an alternating current, usually operate with alternating load, but fixed rotational frequency.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] This is due to the mains' fixed frequency of either 50 Hz (Europe), or 60 Hz (United States).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The engine's crankshaft rotational frequency is chosen so that the mains' frequency is a multiple of it.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] For practical reasons, on typical small generator sets for home use or standby applications (as distinct from continuous operation) this results in crankshaft rotational frequencies of either 25 Hz (1500 per minute) or 30 Hz (1800 per minute).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Larger generator sets, in particular using medium speed engines, operate at synchronous speeds of 500, 514, 600, 720, 750, 900, or 1000 rpm depending on the grid frequency and size of engine.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Diesel engines with a flexible crankshaft refer to internal combustion engines where the crankshaft exhibits a degree of elasticity due to operational stresses, manufacturing tolerances, and material properties.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Unlike a perfectly rigid crankshaft, a flexible one undergoes dynamic deformations due to cyclic combustion forces, inertial loads, and lubrication effects, which can lead to eccentric motion and vibrational displacement.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] This flexibility can impact engine performance by influencing bearing loads, lubrication film distribution, and mechanical wear, potentially reducing efficiency and lifespan.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Advanced modeling techniques, such as Finite Element Analysis (FEA) and Multi-Body Dynamics (MBD), are used to predict and mitigate these effects, enabling better engine design, improved fuel efficiency, and enhanced durability.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] The flexibility of a crankshaft decreases the mass flow rate of air that goes into cylinders, resulting in an unfavorable higher rate of exhaust emissions like CO.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] A special class of prototype internal combustion piston engines has been developed over several decades with the goal of improving efficiency by reducing heat loss.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] These engines are variously called adiabatic engines (due to better approximation of adiabatic expansion), low heat rejection engines, or high temperature engines.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] They are generally piston engines with combustion chamber parts lined with ceramic thermal barrier coatings.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Some make use of pistons and other parts made of titanium which has a low thermal conductivity and density.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Some designs are able to eliminate the use of a cooling system and associated parasitic losses altogether.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Developing lubricants able to withstand the higher temperatures involved has been a major barrier to commercialization.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] In mid-2010s literature, main development goals for future diesel engines are described as improvements of exhaust emissions, reduction of fuel consumption, and increase of lifespan (2014).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] It is said that the diesel engine, especially the diesel engine for commercial vehicles, will remain the most important vehicle powerplant until the mid-2030s.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Editors assume that the complexity of the diesel engine will increase further (2014).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/diesel-engine-p02] Some editors expect a future convergency of diesel and Otto engines' operating principles due to Otto engine development steps made towards homogeneous charge compression ignition (2017).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] An **explosion** is a rapid expansion in volume of a given amount of matter associated with an extreme outward release of energy, usually with the generation of high temperatures and release of high-pressure gases.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Explosions may also be generated by a slower expansion that would normally not be forceful, but is not allowed to expand, so that when whatever is containing the expansion is broken by the pressure that builds as the matter inside tries to expand, the matter expands forcefully.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] An example of this is a volcanic eruption created by the expansion of magma in a magma chamber as it rises to the surface.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Supersonic explosions created by high explosives are known as detonations and travel through shock waves.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Subsonic explosions are created by low explosives through a slower combustion process known as deflagration.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] For an explosion to occur, there must be a rapid, forceful expansion of matter.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] There are numerous ways this can happen, both naturally and artificially, such as volcanic eruptions, or two objects striking each other at very high speeds, as in an impact event.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Explosive volcanic eruptions occur when magma rises from below, it has dissolved gas in it.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The reduction of pressure as the magma rises causes the gas to bubble out of solution, resulting in a rapid increase in volume, however the size of the magma chamber remains the same.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] This results in pressure buildup that eventually leads to an explosive eruption.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Explosions can also occur outside of Earth in the universe in events such as supernovae, or, more commonly, stellar flares.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Humans are also able to create explosions through the use of explosives, or through nuclear fission or fusion, as in a nuclear weapon.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Explosions frequently occur during bushfires in eucalyptus forests where the volatile oils in the tree tops suddenly combust.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Among the largest known explosions in the universe are supernovae, which occur after the end of life of some types of stars.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Solar flares are an example of common, much less energetic, explosions on the Sun, and presumably on most other stars as well.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The energy source for solar flare activity comes from the tangling of magnetic field lines resulting from the rotation of the Sun's conductive plasma.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Another type of large astronomical explosion occurs when a meteoroid or an asteroid impacts the surface of another object, or explodes in its atmosphere, such as a planet.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] This occurs because the two objects are moving at very high speed relative to each other (a minimum of 11.2 kilometres per second (7.0 mi/s) for an Earth impacting body).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] For example, the Tunguska event of 1908 is believed to have resulted from a meteor air burst.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Black hole mergers, likely involving binary black hole systems, are capable of radiating many solar masses of energy into the universe in a fraction of a second, in the form of gravitational waves.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] This is capable of transmitting ordinary energy and destructive forces to nearby objects, but in the vastness of space, nearby objects are rare.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The gravitational wave observed on 21 May 2019, known as GW190521, produced a merger signal of about 100 ms duration, during which time is it estimated to have radiated away nine solar masses in the form of gravitational energy.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The most common artificial explosives are chemical explosives, usually involving a rapid and violent oxidation reaction that produces large amounts of hot gas.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Gunpowder was the first explosive to be invented and put to use.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Other notable early developments in chemical explosive technology were Frederick Augustus Abel's development of nitrocellulose in 1865 and Alfred Nobel's invention of dynamite in 1866.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Chemical explosions (both intentional and accidental) are often initiated by an electric spark or flame in the presence of oxygen.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Accidental explosions may occur in fuel tanks, rocket engines, etc.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Chemical reactions that cause explosions are typically either unimolecular decomposition reactions or multi-molecular reduction-oxidation (redox) reactions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] A high current electrical fault can create an "electrical explosion" by forming a high-energy electrical arc which rapidly vaporizes metal and insulation material.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] This arc flash hazard is a danger to people working on energized switchgear.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Excessive magnetic pressure within an ultra-strong electromagnet can cause a *magnetic explosion*.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Strictly a physical process, as opposed to chemical or nuclear, e.g., the bursting of a sealed or partially sealed container under internal pressure is often referred to as an explosion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Examples include an overheated boiler or a simple tin can of beans tossed into a fire.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Boiling liquid expanding vapor explosions are one type of mechanical explosion that can occur when a vessel containing a pressurized liquid is ruptured, causing a rapid increase in volume as the liquid evaporates.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Note that the contents of the container may cause a subsequent chemical explosion, the effects of which can be dramatically more serious, such as a propane tank in the midst of a fire.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] In such a case, to the effects of the mechanical explosion when the tank fails are added the effects from the explosion resulting from the released (initially liquid and then almost instantaneously gaseous) propane in the presence of an ignition source.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] For this reason, emergency workers often differentiate between the two events.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] In addition to stellar nuclear explosions, a nuclear weapon is a type of explosive weapon that derives its destructive force from nuclear fission or from a combination of fission and fusion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] As a result, even a nuclear weapon with a small yield is significantly more powerful than the largest conventional explosives available, with a single weapon capable of completely destroying an entire city.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Explosive force is released in a direction perpendicular to the surface of the explosive.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] If a grenade is in mid air during the explosion, the direction of the blast will be 360°.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] In contrast, in a shaped charge the explosive forces are focused to produce a greater local explosion; shaped charges are often used by military to breach doors or walls.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The speed of the reaction is what distinguishes an explosive reaction from an ordinary combustion reaction.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Unless the reaction occurs very rapidly, the thermally expanding gases will be moderately dissipated in the medium, with no large differential in pressure and no explosion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] As a wood fire burns in a fireplace, for example, there certainly is the evolution of heat and the formation of gases, but neither is liberated rapidly enough to build up a sudden substantial pressure differential and then cause an explosion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] This can be likened to the difference between the energy discharge of a battery, which is slow, and that of a flash capacitor like that in a camera flash, which releases its energy all at once.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The generation of heat in large quantities accompanies most explosive chemical reactions.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The exceptions are called entropic explosives and include organic peroxides such as acetone peroxide.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] It is the rapid liberation of heat that causes the gaseous products of most explosive reactions to expand and generate high pressures.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] This rapid generation of high pressures of the released gas constitutes the explosion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The liberation of heat with insufficient rapidity will not cause an explosion.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] For example, although a unit mass of coal yields five times as much heat as a unit mass of nitroglycerin, the coal cannot be used as an explosive (except in the form of coal dust) because the rate at which it yields this heat is quite slow.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] In fact, a substance that burns less rapidly (*i.e.* slow combustion) may actually evolve more total heat than an explosive that detonates rapidly (*i.e.* fast combustion).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] See Heat of Combustion for a more thorough treatment of this topic.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] When a chemical compound is formed from its constituents, heat may either be absorbed or released.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] The quantity of heat absorbed or given off during transformation is called the heat of formation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Heats of formations for solids and gases found in explosive reactions have been determined for a temperature of 25 °C and atmospheric pressure, and are normally given in units of kilojoules per gram-molecule.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] A positive value indicates that heat is absorbed during the formation of the compound from its elements; such a reaction is called an endothermic reaction.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] In explosive technology only materials that are exothermic—that have a net liberation of heat and have a negative heat of formation—are of interest.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Reaction heat is measured under conditions either of constant pressure or constant volume.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] A chemical explosive is a compound or mixture which, upon the application of heat or shock, decomposes or rearranges with extreme rapidity, yielding much gas and heat.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Many substances not ordinarily classed as explosives may do one, or even two, of these things.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] A reaction must be capable of being initiated by the application of shock, heat, or a catalyst (in the case of some explosive chemical reactions) to a small portion of the mass of the explosive material.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] A material in which the first three factors exist cannot be accepted as an explosive unless the reaction can be made to occur when needed.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Fragmentation is the accumulation and projection of particles as the result of a high explosives detonation.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] High velocity, low angle fragments can travel hundreds of metres with enough energy to initiate other surrounding high explosive items, injure or kill personnel, and/or damage vehicles or structures.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] In aerospace engineering, the term rapid unscheduled/unplanned disassembly is humorously used as a euphemism for the explosion of an aircraft or spacecraft.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] It was used by Elon Musk in 2015 after a failure of its Falcon 9 first-stage landing mechanism after it lost control just before landing.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/explosion] Classical Latin *explōdō* means "to hiss a bad actor off the stage", "to drive an actor off the stage by making noise", from *ex-* ("out") + *plaudō* ("to clap; to applaud").
[src:steam-powered-vessel/steam-powered-vessel] Screw-driven steamships generally carry the ship prefix "SS" before their names, meaning 'Steam Ship' (or 'Screw Steamer' i.e.
[src:steam-powered-vessel/steam-powered-vessel] 'screw-driven steamship', or 'Screw Schooner' during the 1870s and 1880s, when sail was also carried), paddle steamers usually carry the prefix "PS" and steamships powered by steam turbine may be prefixed "TS" (turbine ship).
[src:steam-powered-vessel/steam-powered-vessel] The term *steamer* is occasionally used, out of nostalgia, for diesel motor-driven vessels, prefixed "MV".
[src:steam-powered-vessel/steam-powered-vessel] The production of steam by nuclear marine propulsion units is almost exclusively done in aircraft carriers and submarines, due to the regulations limiting distribution and ownership of the radioactive fuels used to power the plants.
